{"title_page": "Cambridge University Eco Racing", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n[[File:Cambridge University Eco-Racing logo 2012.png|350px|thumb|right|Cambridge University Eco-Racing logo]]\n'''Cambridge University Eco Racing''' ('''CUER''') is the UK's leading [[solar car racing]] team. The team of 60 Cambridge students design, build and race [[Solar power|solar-powered]] vehicles. Founded in 2007, their first prototype vehicle, ''Affinity'', became the first solar-powered car to drive legally on [[Roads in the United Kingdom|UK roads]]. The team compete in the biennial [[World Solar Challenge]]. CUER's race vehicle for the 2013 race, ''Resolution'', is known for its innovative tracking plate design, and unusual teardrop shape. Its latest vehicle, ''Evolution'', builds upon this previous design and was entered into the 2015 race, where it became the best UK entry since 2007.\n\n==Background==\nCambridge University Eco Racing is based in the University's [[Cambridge University Engineering Department|Department of Engineering]] and comprises around 60 undergraduate members from several departments of [[Cambridge University]]. As well as having a large student body, the team is strongly supported by a number of academic and industrial advisers, including [[Hermann Hauser]] and [[David Cleevely]].\n\nThe team was founded in 2007 by Martin McBrien, inspired by the solar car team at [[MIT]]. Its first vehicle, ''Affinity'', was designed and constructed in early 2008 and was used as a prototype and display vehicle rather than for serious competition. In June 2008, ''Affinity'' was driven from [[Land's End]] to [[John O'Groats]] to raise awareness of [[sustainable energy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cambridge University Eco Racing solar car drive across Britain|url=http://www.physorg.com/news132409745.html|accessdate=19 April 2011|newspaper=PhysOrg.com|date=11 June 2008}}</ref> As part of the [[Land's End to John o' Groats|End to End]] venture, it was endorsed by the [[Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency]] to legally drive on UK roads, and became the first such vehicle to qualify.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} CUER runs outreach events at local schools and has been featured in a wide range of local, national and international media.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lucas|first=Paul|title=Sun shines on new green car concept|url=http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2008/06/12/sun-shines-on-new-green-car-concept/|accessdate=19 April 2011|newspaper=The Green Car Website|date=12 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005102540/http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2008/06/12/sun-shines-on-new-green-car-concept/|archive-date=5 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, work began on the second generation CUER vehicle, ''Endeavour''. Following design work by a number of students in the Engineering Department, and with the support of the advisory board, the team competed in the 2009 [[World Solar Challenge]], a 3000&nbsp;km marathon across Australia. They came 14th, of 26 competitors, after a battery failure severely hindered their chances of competing effectively. ''Endeavour'''s 2009 entry was launched by [[Jenson Button]] at the Goodwood Festival of Speed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Goodwood Festival of Speed: Jenson Button unveils solar racer|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/goodwood-festival-of-speed/5734374/Goodwood-Festival-of-Speed-Jenson-Button-unveils-solar-racer.html|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nOver the next two years, they continued redesigning and refining Endeavour, resulting in a car with much improved aerodynamic properties and more reliable batteries. The team used [[Computational fluid dynamics|CFD]] simulations to make minor tweaks to the canopy, and tested the car extensively at a local airfield, before heading out to the next World Solar Challenge in October 2011. There, after the hardest race on record due to a combination of thunderstorms and bush fires, they came 25th out of 37 teams.<ref>[http://www.worldsolarchallenge.org/files/17_final_results_document_audited.pdf]</ref>\n\nCUER's newest vehicle and Resolution's successor, Evolution, was its entry into WSC 2015. It implements improvements that addresses many of the stability and structural problems that affected Revolution, while maintaining the new design. The race was used as a proof-of-concept for Evolution's design and to identify areas for improvement in future race cycles. As well as this, Evolution achieved 2,047&nbsp;km on solar power to become the most successful UK entry into WSC since 2007 in terms of distance covered under solar power. The team finished 22nd of 27 Challenger class competitors.\n\n== Vehicles ==\n[[File:affinity-landsend.jpg|right|thumb|300px|''Affinity'' at Land's End, 2008]]\n\n===''Affinity''===\n''Affinity'' was CUER's first vehicle, built as a prototype and based on a shape taken from [[MIT]]'s ''Manta Elite'' solar car. Affinity became the UK's first road legal solar car, successfully driving from Land's End to John o'Groats as part of CUER's \"End to End\" tour in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manta Elite|url=http://solar-cars.scripts.mit.edu/car/mantaelite.php|publisher=MIT Solar Electric Vehicle Team|accessdate=19 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110327135630/http://solar-cars.scripts.mit.edu/car/mantaelite.php#|archive-date=27 March 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimensions (LWH)\n| 5&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;2 x 1 m\n|-\n! Cruising speed\n| 30&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! Top speed\n| 50&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! [[Kerb weight]]\n| 250&nbsp;kg\n|-\n! Chassis\n| Steel [[space frame]]\n|-\n! Solar array power\n| 1&nbsp;kW\n|-\n! Motor Efficiency\n| 80%\n|-\n! [[Coefficient of drag|C<sub>d</sub>]]A\n| 0.19\n|}\n\n===''Endeavour''===\nThe second generation vehicle, designed and built to compete in the [[World Solar Challenge]]. First entering the World Solar Challenge in 2009, the team led by Anthony Law raced across the Outback of Australia marking the team's highest placed finish to date. Endeavour was modified and take to Australia again in 2011 by the team led by Emil Hewage.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimensions (LWH)\n| 5 x 1.8&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;1 m\n|-\n! Cruising speed\n| 45&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! Top speed\n| 70&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! [[Kerb weight]]\n| 230&nbsp;kg\n|-\n! Chassis\n| Aluminium [[space frame]]\n|-\n! Solar array power\n| 1.2&nbsp;kW\n|-\n! Motor efficiency\n| 90%+\n|-\n! [[Coefficient of drag|C<sub>d</sub>]]A\n| 0.14\n|}\n\n===''Resolution''===\nDesigned and built in under 12 months, Resolution's innovative aerodynamic shape breaks away from the classic 'table top' design seen in most entrants to the World Solar Challenge.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimensions (LWH)\n| 4.5 x 0.8&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;1.1 m\n|-\n! Cruising speed\n| 55&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! Top speed\n| 88&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! [[Kerb weight]]\n| 120&nbsp;kg\n|-\n! Chassis\n| Carbon Fibre [[Monocoque]] \n|-\n! Motor efficiency\n| 99%+\n|-\n|}\n\n===''Evolution''===\nEvolution formed an improvement to the design concept which had been pioneered with Resolution\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Dimensions (LWH)\n| 4.5 x 1&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;1 m\n|-\n! Cruising speed\n| 40&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! Top speed\n| 68&nbsp;mph\n|-\n! [[Kerb weight]]\n| 230&nbsp;kg\n|-\n! Chassis\n| Carbon Fibre [[Monocoque]] \n|-\n! Motor efficiency\n| 99%+\n|-\n|}\n\n==Conferences and sponsorship==\nCUER regularly attends industry conferences. They have been represented at the Raymond James\u2019 4th Annual European Investors North American Equities Conference, and the Exhibition of Advanced Manufacturing and Engineering at Hethel Engineering Centre and Marketforce\u2019s \u2018Renewables 2008\u2019. CUER also exhibited in Cambridge at the ARM Partner Meeting, Cambridge Climate\u2019s \u2018Entrepreneurship for a Zero-Carbon Society\u2019 conference and CIR\u2019s \u2018Solar Smart HEAT\u2019 event.\n\nFurther afield, CUER exhibited amongst the Europe\u2019s top 100 [[Cleantech]] companies at the Guardian/Library House Essential Cleantech conference, and presented at \u2018Commercialising Photovoltaics\u2019 organised by Renewables East.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of solar car teams]]\n\n==References==\n{{more footnotes|date=March 2009}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cuer.co.uk/ Cambridge University Eco Racing Website]\n*[http://www.eng.cam.ac.uk Cambridge University Engineering Department]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090301150617/http://www.wsc.org.au/ World Solar Challenge (WSC)]\n\n===Publications===\n*[[Varsity (Cambridge)|Varsity]]: \"Cambridge Abroad\", A. McNally, Dec 2008, p34\n*[http://www.bluesci.org BlueSci]: \"Going Solar: Cambridge University Takes on the Solar Car Challenge\", Jan 2009 p21\n*[http://www.thepress.co.uk/news/2348661.york_man_builds_uks_first_roadlegal_solar_car/ York Press]\n*[http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/cn_news_home/displayarticle.asp?id=323270 Cambridge Evening News]\n*[http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/features/Long-journey-ahead-as-green.4171990.jp Yorkshire Post]\n\n===Websites===\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-33525602 BBC News]\n*[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/c0c64ae8-3635-11dd-8bb8-0000779fd2ac,dwp_uuid=a9543bac-edcc-11db-8584-000b5df10621.html Financial Times Online]\n*[http://www.channel4.com/4car/news/news-story.jsp?news_id=17612 4Car]\n*[http://h20195.www2.hp.com/v2/GetPDF.aspx/4AA2-0901EEW.pdf HP.com]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120429050935/http://www.eei-online.com/news.php?key=1412 East of England International]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2008/09/01/engineer_eco_car_feature.shtml BBC Cambridgeshire]\n*[http://www.liebertonline.com/doi/abs/10.1089/SUS.2008.9952 Sustainability: The Journal of Record]