{"title_page": "Cam (singer)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Cam\n| image            = Country singer Cam at Bra Country Concert.jpg\n| image_upright    = 1.0\n| caption          = Cam performing live in 2016.\n| birth_name       = Camaron Marvel Ochs<ref name=\"burning\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-cams-haunting-new-single-burning-house-20150618|title=Hear Cam's Haunting New Hit Single 'Burning House'|last=Shelburne|first=Craig|date=18 June 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|11|19}}<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n| birth_place      = [[Huntington Beach, California]], U.S.\n| other_names      = <!--Per Template:Infobox person and MOS:MULTINAMES, it is not necessary to list off her names here. Also see WP:BLP.-->\n| occupation       = {{flat list|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| home_town        = [[Lafayette, California]], U.S.\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Adam Weaver<br />|2016}}\n| children         =\n| awards           =\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| label = {{flat list|\n*Rubber Room\n*[[Arista Nashville]]\n}}\n| associated_acts =\n| website = [http://www.camcountry.com/ camcountry.com]}}\n}}\n'''Cam''' (born '''Camaron Marvel Ochs'''; November 19, 1984) is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter. She began her career as a songwriter, composing material for several artists including [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and [[Miley Cyrus]]. In 2010, she released her debut studio album ''[[Heartforward]]'' on an independent record label. Signing with [[Sony Music Entertainment]], she released her debut major label [[extended play|EP]] in March 2015, ''[[Welcome to Cam Country]]'', followed by the studio album ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' later that same year. Her second single \"[[Burning House]]\" is her most commercially successful, peaking at the number two position on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] and [[Country Airplay]]. Spurred by airplay on ''[[The Bobby Bones Show]]'', the song received widespread acclaim, including a Best Country Solo Performance nomination at the [[58th Annual Grammy Awards]] and a Double Platinum certification by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Cam's music is defined by [[country pop]] stylings and varied musical influences.\n\n==Early life==\nCam was born on November 18, 1984 in [[Huntington Beach, California]],<ref name=\"rocha\">{{cite news|last1=Rocha|first1=Michael James|title=Country singer Cam on her musical journey \u2014 from Oceanside to Nashville to the Grammys|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/entertainment/music/sd-et-music-cam-20171127-story.html|accessdate=29 November 2017|newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> and was raised in [[Lafayette, California]], a suburb in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].<ref name=SAENash>{{cite news|last1=Malone|first1=Dana|title=Pathway to a record deal: Hard work, circumstance and originality take Cam Ochs 'Down The Road'|url=http://sportsandentertainmentnashville.com/pathway-to-a-record-deal-hard-work-circumstance-and-originality-take-camaron-ochs-down-the-road/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Sports and Entertainment Nashville|date=5 September 2014}}</ref> She also spent time in [[Oceanside, California]], where her grandparents operated a [[ranch]]. They helped develop Cam's appreciation for country music, listening to and performing it regularly.<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount>{{cite magazine|last1=Dauphin|first1=Chuck|title=Welcome To Cam Country: Arista Nashville Singer Has a Short Name, Potentially Long Career|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6531920/welcome-to-cam-country-arista-nashville-singer-has-a-short-name|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=16 April 2015}}</ref> Pursuing music throughout high school and college, she sang in various choral groups.<ref name=OCOmayinspire>{{cite news|last1=Schadewald|first1=Amber|title=Oakland's Camaron Ochs may inspire folk-pop Barbie|url=http://www.sfbg.com/noise/2010/03/16/oaklands-camaron-ochs-may-inspire-folk-pop-barbie|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=San Francisco Bay Guardian|date=16 March 2010}}</ref> This included performing in the Contra Costa Children's Chorus, where she learned to sing in 14 languages. She attended the [[University of California, Davis]] as an [[undergraduate education|undergraduate student]], studying psychology.<ref name=\"Smoldering Ballad\">{{cite magazine|last1=Roland|first1=Tom|title=Country Singer Cam Dreams Up a Smoldering Ballad With 'Burning House'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/6633599/country-singer-cam-dreams-up-a-smoldering-ballad-with-burning-house|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> There, she formed an all-female collegiate [[a cappella]] group called [[The Spokes]] and learned to play the [[guitar]] while studying abroad in the [[Netherlands]]. She developed confidence in playing the instrument on a trip to [[Nepal]]. Taking residency in a rural mountain community, she lived for several weeks with limited electricity and basic needs; in addition, she developed a friendship with various Canadian musicians and started playing the guitar more consistently. In a 2010 interview, Cam stated that she grew more confident in playing once from the trip.<ref name=OCOmayinspire/>\n\nFollowing college, she sporadically performed music but mostly pursued other interests. This included work in research labs, including one at [[Stanford University]]. Yet she remained conflicted about the choices she made.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Patrick|title=On the Verge: Cam|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/ontheverge/2015/11/01/on-the-verge-cam-burning-house/74596536/|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> A meeting with a college professor influenced Cam's choice to embark on a full-fledged music career. The professor said to her, \"Just picture yourself at 80 years old. Looking back at your life, what would you regret not doing: music or psychology?'\"<ref name=\"USA Today\"/><ref name=\"Billboard Interview\">{{cite magazine|last1=Hight|first1=Jewly|title=Why 'Burning House' Singer Cam Gave Up Psychology for Country Music|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/6708058/cam-burning-house-women-country-music-psychology|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2010\u20132014: Early beginnings===\nIn 2010, Cam released her debut studio album titled ''[[Heartforward]]'' via the independent Rubber Room label. Credited to her full name of Camaron Ochs, the album contained contemporary [[pop music|pop]] songs.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web|last1=Deming|first1=Mark|title=Cam: Biography and History|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cam-mn0003380333/biography|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Amber Schadewald of the ''[[San Francisco Bay Guardian]]'' called the album a brand of [[Folk rock|folk pop]] that \"is light and sweet, with genuine lyrics that ask listeners to live with their 'heartforward'\". Songs written for the project were based on experiences from her trip to Nepal. She promoted ''Heartforward'' through performances in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and [[San Francisco, California]], including shows at the Stork Club and Mama Buzz.<ref name=OCOmayinspire/>\n\nCam soon moved to [[Los Angeles, California]], and began collaborating with songwriter and producer [[Tyler Johnson (music)|Tyler Johnson]]. She recorded some demos with Johnson in an attempt to attract [[Faith Hill]], eventually leading to the recordings being heard by [[Tim McGraw]]'s manager.<ref name=SAENash/> Her song \"Fall Madly in Love with You\" was chosen as a track for ''[[Cut to Impress]]'', the 2013 debut album from [[Maggie Rose]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yes they Cam|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=295480|website=HitsDailyDouble|publisher=Hits Digital Ventures|accessdate=October 7, 2015|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=GlamourMag>{{cite news|last1=Radloff|first1=Jessica|title=Here's What Really Happened Behind the Scenes at the ACM Awards Last Night|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/blogs/obsessed/2015/04/acm-awards-video-photos-red-carpet|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Glamour Magazine|date=20 April 2015}}</ref> [[Miley Cyrus]] also recorded one of Cam's songs, \"Maybe You're Right\", on her 2013 album ''[[Bangerz]]''.<ref name=SwedishHDse>{{cite news|last1=Lindqvist|first1=Stefan|title=Camaron Ochs sjunger med Helsingborgsband|url=http://www.hd.se/noje/2013/11/30/camaron-ochs-sjunger-med-helsingborgsband/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=HD.se|date=30 November 2013|language=Swedish}}</ref> The success of these songs led her to  move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; there, began writing music for other artists, turning down a publishing deal in attempt to prove herself on her own.<ref name=SAENash/><ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron Ochs keeps it country with rootsy, organic debut|url=http://forthecountryrecord.com/2014/02/12/cameron-ochs-keeps-it-country-with-rootsy-organic-debut-review/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=For The Country Record|date=12 February 2014}}</ref> She launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign in 2013 to produce 10 songs with Johnson.<ref name=StamTodayLocals>{{cite news|last1=Inglis|first1=Nicole|title=Country star on the rise with support from Steamboat locals|url=http://www.steamboattoday.com/news/2012/dec/19/country-star-rise-support-steamboat-locals/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Steamboat Today|date=20 December 2012}}</ref> The campaign was supported by producer [[Jeff Bhasker]], known best for his work with artists that include [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Fun (band)|fun.]], [[Bruno Mars]], and [[Pink (singer)|P!nk]].<ref name=SAENash/> The same year Cam toured Denmark and Sweden with [[Helsingborg]] band Karavan, having previously collaborated with Anders Mouridsen of the group while in Los Angeles.<ref name=SwedishHDse/>\n\nCam released a [[single (music)|single]] in 2013 titled \"Down This Road\" with the encouragement of manager Lindsay Marias. Through a photo posted on [[Instagram]], local radio director Michael Bryan discovered the song and played it on the air. According to Cam, radio airplay of the single helped her choose which label she wanted to sign to. Ultimately, she chose to meet with [[Doug Morris]], the director of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. She flew to the label's headquarters in [[New York City]] to meet with him.<ref name=SwedishHDse/> Using only an [[acoustic guitar]], she sang a song she had already been developing, \"[[Burning House]]\". Morris started humming along to the chorus and stated, \"This is the reason why I got into the music business.\" He would later ask her to perform the song at the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rau|first1=Nate|title=Sony Music CEO Doug Morris touts Nashville up-and-comers|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/07/24/sony-music-ceo-doug-morris-touts-nashville-up-and-comers/30641039/|website=[[The Tennessean]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> She was soon signed to Sony's country division, [[Arista Nashville]] in 2014<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits>{{cite magazine|title=Tomorrow's Hits: The Avener's 'Fade Out Lines,' Cam and Young Rising Sons|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6472726/tomorrow-hits-avener-cam-young-rising-sons|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=13 February 2015}}</ref> and toured nationally with [[Dan + Shay]] that same year on their ''Where It All Began'' tour.<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits/>\n\n===2015\u2013present: Breakthrough===\nIn early 2015, Arista Nashville released Cam's first single for them, \"[[My Mistake (Cam song)|My Mistake]]\".<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits/> In March, the song debuted at No. 58 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Country Airplay]] chart.<ref name=BillboardBlackberry>{{cite magazine|last1=Jessen|first1=Wade|title=Blackberry Smoke's 'Roses' Blooms at No. 1 on Top Country Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6479936/blackberry-smoke-top-country-albums|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=19 February 2015}}</ref> The song peaked at number 52 only a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Country Adds|url=http://www.country103.ca/new-music-added/|website=Country 103|accessdate=28 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106231408/http://www.country103.ca/new-music-added/#|archive-date=2016-01-06|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Still using her full name (Camaron Ochs) during the single's promotion, she ultimately shortened it to \"Cam\" because some people found her last name \"too hard to pronounce\".<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount/> \"My Mistake\" preceded Cam's debut [[extended play|EP]], ''[[Welcome to Cam Country]]'', released in March 2015. It contained four songs, with Bhasker and Johnson serving as producers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Allers|first1=Hannahlee|title=Cam Releases Debut EP|url=http://theboot.com/cam-welcome-to-cam-country-ep/|website=The Boot|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/press/cam/97966/arista-nashville-recording-artist-cam-reveals-debut-ep-exclusively-spotify|title=Arista Nashville Recording Artist Cam Reveals Debut EP, Exclusively on Spotify|work=Sony Music Nashville|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626130318/http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/press/cam/97966/arista-nashville-recording-artist-cam-reveals-debut-ep-exclusively-spotify|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> It peaked at No.  31 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart, No. 88 on the [[Billboard 200]], and No. 5 on the [[Top Heatseekers]] survey.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Welcome to Cam Country'' - Cam: Awards|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-cam-country-mw0002836605/awards|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"Burning House\" served as her next single. She performed the song live on the radio program ''[[The Bobby Bones Show]]'', which attracted and fueled attention to the song.<ref name=\"burning\"/> [[Sony Music Entertainment]], of which Arista Nashville is a division, then arranged a meeting and decided to release the track as a single on June 16, 2015 after the song had initial success on the [[iTunes]] charts.<ref name=\"Smoldering Ballad\"/> \"Burning House\" became a top-five hit on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Songs|country songs]] and country airplay charts.<ref name=\"Top Five\">{{cite magazine|last1=Asker|first1=Jim|title=Cam & Emily Ann Roberts' Versions of 'Burning House' Are Both in the Hot Country Songs Top Five|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6820766/cam-emily-ann-roberts-burning-house-charts|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> It also was the highest-selling female country song of 2015, selling more than 500,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Watch Cam Cap Off Smoldering Year With Live 'Burning House'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-cam-cap-off-smoldering-year-with-live-burning-house-20151216|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> In addition, the song received a nomination from the 2016 [[Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"Best Country Albums\">{{cite magazine|title=Cam, \"Burning House\" - 25 Best Country Songs of 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/25-best-country-songs-of-2015-20151214/cam-burning-house-20151214|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The success of the song led to the release of her first Arista Nashville album ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' on December 11, 2015. Also produced largely by Bhasker and Johnson, it consisted of 11 tracks all co-written by Cam, including all of the songs from the EP.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reuter|first1=Annie|title=Cam Announces Title, Release Date for Major Label Debut   Read More: Cam Announces Title, Release Date for Major Label Debut|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-debut-album-untamed/|website=[[Taste of Country]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> It debuted at number two on the Top Country Albums chart and was the highest-selling debut country studio album of 2015.<ref name=\"Top Five\"/> ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album at number 15 on their list of the \"40 Best Country Albums of 2015\". The magazine commented, \"For an artist at the start of career, Cam already sounds like one of the most secure in the game.\"<ref name=\"Best Country Albums\"/> \"[[Mayday (Cam song)|Mayday]]\" was released as the album's third single in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carr|first1=Courtney|title=Cam Selects \u2018Mayday\u2019 as New Single [LISTEN]|url=http://theboot.com/cam-mayday-song-single/|website=The Boot|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> It was a minor Top 40 hit on the country charts, peaking at number 36 on ''Billboard'' Country Airplay.\n\nIn October 2017, Cam announced a new single titled [[Diane (Cam song)|\"Diane\"]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/hear-cams-jolene-inspired-new-song-diane-w510372|title=Hear Cam's Supercharged, 'Jolene'-Inspired New Song 'Diane'|last=Betts|first=Stephen L.|date=October 27, 2017|work=Rolling Stone Country|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> She promoted the song with several live performances including on [[Good Morning America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countryliving.com/life/entertainment/a19681578/cam-diane-song/|title=Watch Dolly Parton Surprise Country Singer Cam On 'Good Morning America'|last=Matthews|first=Lauren|date=4 April 2018|work=Country Living|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8343549/late-late-show-cam-diane|title=Cam Gives Mesmerizing Performance of 'Diane' on 'The Late Late Show'|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=17 April 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> and as a duet with a contestant on [[American Idol (season 16)|season 16 of ''American Idol'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboot.com/cam-american-idol-effie-passero-diane-shannon-ohara-burning-house/|title=Cam Duets with 'American Idol' Contestants on 'Diane,' 'Burning House'|last=Stefano|first=Angela|date=17 April 2018|work=The Boot|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In April 2018, \"Diane\" was added to the [[BBC Radio 2]] A-list and hit No. 1 on iTunes for 5 weeks. Also in 2017, Cam, along with [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and Tyler Johnson, co-wrote the song \"Palace\" for Smith's 2017 album ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'' and providing background vocals and guitar to the track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/cam-wrote-sam-smith-song-we-had-same-heartache/|title=Country Star Cam on Writing a Song for Sam Smith's New Album: We Had the 'Same Heartache'|last=Nelson|first=Jeff|date=3 November 2017|work=People|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The song saw international success and was highlighted in the Holiday \"Sway\" commercial for [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] which led to its reaching No. 1 on the Billboard Top TV Commercials Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8093860/sam-smith-palace-apple-ad-top-tv-commercials-chart-number-one|title=Sam Smith's 'Palace' Hits No. 1 on Top TV Commercials Chart for December|last=Zellner|first=Xander|date=11 January 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The widespread embrace of \"Palace\" included much international success, specifically in [[Japan]], where Smith performed the song on multiple TV talk shows. Cam opened for Smith on the Summer US leg of his 2018 The Thrill Of It All Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-joins-sam-smiths-thrill-of-it-all-tour-629146/|title=Cam Joins Sam Smith's Thrill of It All Tour|last=Betts|first=Stephen L.|date=7 June 2018|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Cam has also shared the stage with [[Tim McGraw]] and [[Faith Hill]] on their [[Soul2Soul: The World Tour|Soul2Soul Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/tim-mcgraw-faith-hills-soul2soul-tour-taps-devin-dawson-caitlyn-smith-127866/|title=Tim McGraw, Faith Hill's Soul2Soul Tour Taps Devin Dawson, Caitlyn Smith|last=Parton|first=Chris|date=19 March 2018|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> as well as [[Harry Styles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/harry-styles-invited-cam-open-nashville-concert-better-than-hype/|title=Harry Styles Invited Country Star Cam to Open His Nashville Show: 'He's Even Better Than All the Hype'|last=Nelson|first=Jeff|date=29 September 2017|work=People|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Cam released a new single entitled \"Road to Happiness\", which did not chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-road-to-happiness/|title=Cam Ponders the Real Meaning of Joy in 'Road to Happiness'|last=Whitaker|first=Sterling|date=13 July 2018|work=Taste of Country|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In 2019, she provided vocals for [[Diplo]]'s song \"[[So Long (Diplo song)|So Long]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-cam-so-long-thomas-wesley-828677/|title=Song You Need to Know: Diplo and Cam, 'So Long'|last=Freeman|first=Jon|last2=Freeman|first2=Jon|date=2019-05-02|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In February 2020, she released the song \"Til There's Nothing Left\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-till-theres-nothing-left-952115/|title=Cam Addresses Sex and Swagger on New Song, 'Till There's Nothing Left'|last=Freeman|first=Jon|last2=Freeman|first2=Jon|date=2020-02-13|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nCam was exposed to classic country music at an early age from the time spent on her grandparents' ranch. They introduced her to the musical sounds of [[Patsy Cline]], [[Bonnie Raitt]] and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount/> She was largely influenced by the vocal phrasing of Cline and [[Ray Charles]]. She also developed an appreciation for the [[Dixie Chicks]] and the [[Indigo Girls]], commenting that she was \"so into those female harmonies\". She additionally cites [[Bob Dylan]], [[Joni Mitchell]], and [[Randy Newman]] as influences on her songwriting style.<ref name=\"Billboard Interview\"/> Although she has a variety of musical influences, Cam stated that country music is where she felt most connected to. In a 2015 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', she explained her reasoning: \"I grew up singing in a lot of different languages and a lot of world music choirs, so I have a lot of musical influences. But the songwriting structure of country music is the standard in my mind. ... That structure seems to feel the most homey to me.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Cam - 10 New Country Artists You Need to Know: Spring 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-new-country-artists-you-need-to-know-spring-2015-20150505/cam-20150505|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn September 2015, Cam became engaged to Adam Weaver, a business broker with First Choice Business Brokers in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Laura|title=Cam Shows Off New Bling|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-engaged/|website=Taste of Country|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, the couple married in a small ceremony in a California desert.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Danielle|title=See Cam's Stunning Wedding Album!|url=http://people.com/country/cam-wedding-album-marries-adam-weaver/|website=People|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> In December 2019, she gave birth to her first child, Lucy. Shortly after giving birth, Cam posted on social media that she was a \"breech at 39wks, a next-day c-section (ouch) & here we are... three of us now.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Iasimone |first1=Ashley |title=Cam Gives Birth to Baby Lucy Marvel: See the Photos |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8546960/cam-baby-birth-announcement |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nCam is a vocal advocate for music education and inclusion. She spoke on the psychology of music in her 2017 TEDx Talk at the University of Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/5-things-we-learned-from-cams-tedx-talk-193313/|title=5 Things We Learned From Cam's TEDx Talk|last=Parton|first=Chris|date=7 March 2017|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Cam is on the [[Academy of Country Music]] (ACM) Board and was invited to join [[The Recording Academy]]'s Task Force on Diversity and Inclusion in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/recording-academy-names-diversity-and-inclusion-task-force-members/|title= Recording Academy Names Diversity And Inclusion Task Force Members|date=9 May 2018|work=Grammy.com|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In 2018, Cam joined the speaker list on [[Hello Sunshine (company)|Hello Sunshine]] x Together Live's touring event<ref>{{cite web|url=http://togetherlive.com/about/|title= Our Stories Travel|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Cam discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Heartforward]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' (2015)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Recipient/Nominated work\n!Association\n!Award\n!Result\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"| 2016\n|rowspan=\"4\"| \"[[Burning House]]\"\n|[[58th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\n|[[Best Country Solo Performance]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" {{Nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|title = Grammy Nominations 2016: See the Full List of Nominees{{!}} Billboard|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6785974/grammy-nominations-2016-full-list|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| [[Academy of Country Music|ACM Awards]]\n|Single Record of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\">{{cite web|title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 51st ACADEMY OF COUNTRY MUSIC AWARDS\u00ae|url=http://www.acmcountry.com/news?n_id=954|website=[[Academy of Country Music]]|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Song of the Year\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=The ACM Awards: Nominees|url=http://www.acmawards.com/nominees|website=[[Academy of Country Music]]|accessdate=20 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308114318/http://www.acmawards.com/nominees|archivedate=8 March 2016|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n|Video of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Cam\n|New Female Vocalist of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\"/>\n|-\n| [[American Music Awards of 2016|American Music Awards]]\n| Favorite Female Country Artist\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=American Music Awards Nominations 2016: See Full List of Nominees |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/american-music-awards-nominations-2016-full-list-nominees/story?id=42647918 |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[Burning House]]\"\n|rowspan=2|[[Country Music Association|CMA Awards]]\n|Song of the Year\n|<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web |title=Past Winners and Nominees: Cam |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=74N0Q6J56D7M6H5CF18CX651D87L666415F225642LQA5VC53SWVZ5R0B3BAH34V0P6POGRC1ZR2H0N1E6FTGBBCC5HNQ93B15U03IN30B6R2RQ14Y5BH4H45CD9650S |website=[[Country Music Association Awards]] |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Music Video of the Year\n|<ref name=\"CMA\"/>\n|-\n| 2017\n| Cam\n| ACM Awards\n| New Female Vocalist of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n'''Supporting act'''\n*Strait Vegas Tour (2017) with [[George Strait]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2016/11/17/george-strait-adds-8-more-vegas-tour-dates-to-2017-schedule/ | title=George Strait Adds 8 More Vegas Tour Dates to 2017 Schedule | work=Nash Country Daily | date=November 17, 2016 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Somewhere on a Beach Tour]] (2016) with [[Dierks Bentley]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tasteofcountry.com/dierks-bentley-2016-somewhere-on-a-beach-tour-dates/ | title=Dierks Bentley announces 2016 Somewhere on a Beach Tour | publisher=[[Taste of Country]] | date=January 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Headlining'''\n* The Burning House Tour (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/cam-plots-headlining-burning-house-tour-w436831|title=Cam Plots Headlining Burning House Tour|first=Stephen L.|last=Betts|date=29 August 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* Best Coast Tour (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/cam-announces-2017-best-coast-tour-w506118|title=Cam Unveils 2017 Best Coast Tour of California, Pacific Northwest|first=Brittney|last=McKenna|date=28 September 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* Listening Room Series (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-plots-stripped-down-listening-room-series-tour-117086/|title= Cam Plots Stripped-Down \u2018Listening Room Series\u2019 Tour|first=Jon|last=Freeman|date=13 March 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* \"Diane\" European Tour (2018)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/CAM-Announces-2019-Summer-European-Tour-20190603 | title=CAM Announces 2019 Summer European Tour | work=Broadway World | date=June 3, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n* Oh the Places We'll Go Tour (2019)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.antimusic.com/news/19/June/04Cam_Announces_The_Oh,_The_Places_Well_Go_Summer_Tour.shtml | title=Cam Announces The Oh, The Places We'll Go! Summer Tour | work=Anti Music | date=June 4, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.camcountry.com}}\n\n{{Cam}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cam}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Arista Nashville artists]]\n[[Category:American female country singers]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, California]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:University of California, Davis alumni]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Cam\n| image            = Country singer Cam at Bra Country Concert.jpg\n| image_upright    = 1.0\n| caption          = Cam performing live in 2016.\n| birth_name       = Camaron Marvel Ochs<ref name=\"burning\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-cams-haunting-new-single-burning-house-20150618|title=Hear Cam's Haunting New Hit Single 'Burning House'|last=Shelburne|first=Craig|date=18 June 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|11|19}}<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n| birth_place      = [[Huntington Beach, California]], U.S.\n| other_names      = <!--Per Template:Infobox person and MOS:MULTINAMES, it is not necessary to list off her names here. Also see WP:BLP.-->\n| occupation       = {{flat list|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| home_town        = [[Lafayette, California]], U.S.\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Adam Weaver<br />|2016}}\n| children         =\n| awards           =\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| label = {{flat list|\n*Rubber Room\n*[[Arista Nashville]]\n}}\n| associated_acts =\n| website = [http://www.camcountry.com/ camcountry.com]}}\n}}\n'''Cam''' (born '''Camaron Marvel Ochs'''; November 19, 1984) is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter. She began her career as a songwriter, composing material for several artists including [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and [[Miley Cyrus]]. In 2010, she released her debut studio album ''[[Heartforward]]'' on an independent record label. Signing with [[Sony Music Entertainment]], she released her debut major label [[extended play|EP]] in March 2015, ''[[Welcome to Cam Country]]'', followed by the studio album ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' later that same year. Her second single \"[[Burning House]]\" is her most commercially successful, peaking at the number two position on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] and [[Country Airplay]]. Spurred by airplay on ''[[The Bobby Bones Show]]'', the song received widespread acclaim, including a Best Country Solo Performance nomination at the [[58th Annual Grammy Awards]] and a Double Platinum certification by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Cam's music is defined by [[country pop]] stylings and varied musical influences.\n\n==Early life==\nCam was born on November 18, 1984 in [[Huntington Beach, California]],<ref name=\"rocha\">{{cite news|last1=Rocha|first1=Michael James|title=Country singer Cam on her musical journey \u2014 from Oceanside to Nashville to the Grammys|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/entertainment/music/sd-et-music-cam-20171127-story.html|accessdate=29 November 2017|newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> and was raised in [[Lafayette, California]], a suburb in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].<ref name=SAENash>{{cite news|last1=Malone|first1=Dana|title=Pathway to a record deal: Hard work, circumstance and originality take Cam Ochs 'Down The Road'|url=http://sportsandentertainmentnashville.com/pathway-to-a-record-deal-hard-work-circumstance-and-originality-take-camaron-ochs-down-the-road/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Sports and Entertainment Nashville|date=5 September 2014}}</ref> She also spent time in [[Oceanside, California]], where her grandparents operated a [[ranch]]. They helped develop Cam's appreciation for country music, listening to and performing it regularly.<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount>{{cite magazine|last1=Dauphin|first1=Chuck|title=Welcome To Cam Country: Arista Nashville Singer Has a Short Name, Potentially Long Career|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6531920/welcome-to-cam-country-arista-nashville-singer-has-a-short-name|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=16 April 2015}}</ref> Pursuing music throughout high school and college, she sang in various choral groups.<ref name=OCOmayinspire>{{cite news|last1=Schadewald|first1=Amber|title=Oakland's Camaron Ochs may inspire folk-pop Barbie|url=http://www.sfbg.com/noise/2010/03/16/oaklands-camaron-ochs-may-inspire-folk-pop-barbie|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=San Francisco Bay Guardian|date=16 March 2010}}</ref> This included performing in the Contra Costa Children's Chorus, where she learned to sing in 14 languages. She attended the [[University of California, Davis]] as an [[undergraduate education|undergraduate student]], studying psychology.<ref name=\"Smoldering Ballad\">{{cite magazine|last1=Roland|first1=Tom|title=Country Singer Cam Dreams Up a Smoldering Ballad With 'Burning House'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/6633599/country-singer-cam-dreams-up-a-smoldering-ballad-with-burning-house|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> There, she formed an all-female collegiate [[a cappella]] group called [[The Spokes]] and learned to play the [[guitar]] while studying abroad in the [[Netherlands]]. She developed confidence in playing the instrument on a trip to [[Nepal]]. Taking residency in a rural mountain community, she lived for several weeks with limited electricity and basic needs; in addition, she developed a friendship with various Canadian musicians and started playing the guitar more consistently. In a 2010 interview, Cam stated that she grew more confident in playing once from the trip.<ref name=OCOmayinspire/>\n\nFollowing college, she sporadically performed music but mostly pursued other interests. This included work in research labs, including one at [[Stanford University]]. Yet she remained conflicted about the choices she made.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Patrick|title=On the Verge: Cam|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/ontheverge/2015/11/01/on-the-verge-cam-burning-house/74596536/|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> A meeting with a college professor influenced Cam's choice to embark on a full-fledged music career. The professor said to her, \"Just picture yourself at 80 years old. Looking back at your life, what would you regret not doing: music or psychology?'\"<ref name=\"USA Today\"/><ref name=\"Billboard Interview\">{{cite magazine|last1=Hight|first1=Jewly|title=Why 'Burning House' Singer Cam Gave Up Psychology for Country Music|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/6708058/cam-burning-house-women-country-music-psychology|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2010\u20132014: Early beginnings===\nIn 2010, Cam released her debut studio album titled ''[[Heartforward]]'' via the independent Rubber Room label. Credited to her full name of Camaron Ochs, the album contained contemporary [[pop music|pop]] songs.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web|last1=Deming|first1=Mark|title=Cam: Biography and History|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/cam-mn0003380333/biography|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Amber Schadewald of the ''[[San Francisco Bay Guardian]]'' called the album a brand of [[Folk rock|folk pop]] that \"is light and sweet, with genuine lyrics that ask listeners to live with their 'heartforward'\". Songs written for the project were based on experiences from her trip to Nepal. She promoted ''Heartforward'' through performances in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and [[San Francisco, California]], including shows at the Stork Club and Mama Buzz.<ref name=OCOmayinspire/>\n\nCam soon moved to [[Los Angeles, California]], and began collaborating with songwriter and producer [[Tyler Johnson (music)|Tyler Johnson]]. She recorded some demos with Johnson in an attempt to attract [[Faith Hill]], eventually leading to the recordings being heard by [[Tim McGraw]]'s manager.<ref name=SAENash/> Her song \"Fall Madly in Love with You\" was chosen as a track for ''[[Cut to Impress]]'', the 2013 debut album from [[Maggie Rose]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yes they Cam|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=295480|website=HitsDailyDouble|publisher=Hits Digital Ventures|accessdate=October 7, 2015|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=GlamourMag>{{cite news|last1=Radloff|first1=Jessica|title=Here's What Really Happened Behind the Scenes at the ACM Awards Last Night|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/blogs/obsessed/2015/04/acm-awards-video-photos-red-carpet|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Glamour Magazine|date=20 April 2015}}</ref> [[Miley Cyrus]] also recorded one of Cam's songs, \"Maybe You're Right\", on her 2013 album ''[[Bangerz]]''.<ref name=SwedishHDse>{{cite news|last1=Lindqvist|first1=Stefan|title=Camaron Ochs sjunger med Helsingborgsband|url=http://www.hd.se/noje/2013/11/30/camaron-ochs-sjunger-med-helsingborgsband/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=HD.se|date=30 November 2013|language=Swedish}}</ref> The success of these songs led her to  move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; there, began writing music for other artists, turning down a publishing deal in attempt to prove herself on her own.<ref name=SAENash/><ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron Ochs keeps it country with rootsy, organic debut|url=http://forthecountryrecord.com/2014/02/12/cameron-ochs-keeps-it-country-with-rootsy-organic-debut-review/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=For The Country Record|date=12 February 2014}}</ref> She launched a [[Kickstarter]] campaign in 2013 to produce 10 songs with Johnson.<ref name=StamTodayLocals>{{cite news|last1=Inglis|first1=Nicole|title=Country star on the rise with support from Steamboat locals|url=http://www.steamboattoday.com/news/2012/dec/19/country-star-rise-support-steamboat-locals/|accessdate=22 April 2015|publisher=Steamboat Today|date=20 December 2012}}</ref> The campaign was supported by producer [[Jeff Bhasker]], known best for his work with artists that include [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Fun (band)|fun.]], [[Bruno Mars]], and [[Pink (singer)|P!nk]].<ref name=SAENash/> The same year Cam toured Denmark and Sweden with [[Helsingborg]] band Karavan, having previously collaborated with Anders Mouridsen of the group while in Los Angeles.<ref name=SwedishHDse/>\n\nCam released a [[single (music)|single]] in 2013 titled \"Down This Road\" with the encouragement of manager Lindsay Marias. Through a photo posted on [[Instagram]], local radio director Michael Bryan discovered the song and played it on the air. According to Cam, radio airplay of the single helped her choose which label she wanted to sign to. Ultimately, she chose to meet with [[Doug Morris]], the director of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. She flew to the label's headquarters in [[New York City]] to meet with him.<ref name=SwedishHDse/> Using only an [[acoustic guitar]], she sang a song she had already been developing, \"[[Burning House]]\". Morris started humming along to the chorus and stated, \"This is the reason why I got into the music business.\" He would later ask her to perform the song at the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rau|first1=Nate|title=Sony Music CEO Doug Morris touts Nashville up-and-comers|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/07/24/sony-music-ceo-doug-morris-touts-nashville-up-and-comers/30641039/|website=[[The Tennesseean]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> She was soon signed to Sony's country division, [[Arista Nashville]] in 2014<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits>{{cite magazine|title=Tomorrow's Hits: The Avener's 'Fade Out Lines,' Cam and Young Rising Sons|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6472726/tomorrow-hits-avener-cam-young-rising-sons|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=13 February 2015}}</ref> and toured nationally with [[Dan + Shay]] that same year on their ''Where It All Began'' tour.<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits/>\n\n===2015\u2013present: Breakthrough===\nIn early 2015, Arista Nashville released Cam's first single for them, \"[[My Mistake (Cam song)|My Mistake]]\".<ref name=BilboarTomorrowhits/> In March, the song debuted at No. 58 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Country Airplay]] chart.<ref name=BillboardBlackberry>{{cite magazine|last1=Jessen|first1=Wade|title=Blackberry Smoke's 'Roses' Blooms at No. 1 on Top Country Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6479936/blackberry-smoke-top-country-albums|accessdate=22 April 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=19 February 2015}}</ref> The song peaked at number 52 only a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Country Adds|url=http://www.country103.ca/new-music-added/|website=Country 103|accessdate=28 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106231408/http://www.country103.ca/new-music-added/#|archive-date=2016-01-06|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Still using her full name (Camaron Ochs) during the single's promotion, she ultimately shortened it to \"Cam\" because some people found her last name \"too hard to pronounce\".<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount/> \"My Mistake\" preceded Cam's debut [[extended play|EP]], ''[[Welcome to Cam Country]]'', released in March 2015. It contained four songs, with Bhasker and Johnson serving as producers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Allers|first1=Hannahlee|title=Cam Releases Debut EP|url=http://theboot.com/cam-welcome-to-cam-country-ep/|website=The Boot|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/press/cam/97966/arista-nashville-recording-artist-cam-reveals-debut-ep-exclusively-spotify|title=Arista Nashville Recording Artist Cam Reveals Debut EP, Exclusively on Spotify|work=Sony Music Nashville|accessdate=25 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626130318/http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/press/cam/97966/arista-nashville-recording-artist-cam-reveals-debut-ep-exclusively-spotify|archive-date=26 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> It peaked at No.  31 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart, No. 88 on the [[Billboard 200]], and No. 5 on the [[Top Heatseekers]] survey.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Welcome to Cam Country'' - Cam: Awards|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-cam-country-mw0002836605/awards|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"Burning House\" served as her next single. She performed the song live on the radio program ''[[The Bobby Bones Show]]'', which attracted and fueled attention to the song.<ref name=\"burning\"/> [[Sony Music Entertainment]], of which Arista Nashville is a divison, then arranged a meeting and decided to release the track as a single on June 16, 2015 after the song had initial success on the [[iTunes]] charts.<ref name=\"Smoldering Ballad\"/> \"Burning House\" became a top-five hit on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Songs|country songs]] and country airplay charts.<ref name=\"Top Five\">{{cite magazine|last1=Asker|first1=Jim|title=Cam & Emily Ann Roberts' Versions of 'Burning House' Are Both in the Hot Country Songs Top Five|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6820766/cam-emily-ann-roberts-burning-house-charts|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> It also was the highest-selling female country song of 2015, selling more than 500,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Watch Cam Cap Off Smoldering Year With Live 'Burning House'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-cam-cap-off-smoldering-year-with-live-burning-house-20151216|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> In addition, the song received a nomination from the 2016 [[Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"Best Country Albums\">{{cite magazine|title=Cam, \"Burning House\" - 25 Best Country Songs of 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/25-best-country-songs-of-2015-20151214/cam-burning-house-20151214|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The success of the song led to the release of her first Arista Nashville album ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' on December 11, 2015. Also produced largely by Bhasker and Johnson, it consisted of 11 tracks all co-written by Cam, including all of the songs from the EP.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reuter|first1=Annie|title=Cam Announces Title, Release Date for Major Label Debut   Read More: Cam Announces Title, Release Date for Major Label Debut|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-debut-album-untamed/|website=[[Taste of Country]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> It debuted at number two on the Top Country Albums chart and was the highest-selling debut country studio album of 2015.<ref name=\"Top Five\"/> ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album at number 15 on their list of the \"40 Best Country Albums of 2015\". The magazine commented, \"For an artist at the start of career, Cam already sounds like one of the most secure in the game.\"<ref name=\"Best Country Albums\"/> \"[[Mayday (Cam song)|Mayday]]\" was released as the album's third single in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carr|first1=Courtney|title=Cam Selects \u2018Mayday\u2019 as New Single [LISTEN]|url=http://theboot.com/cam-mayday-song-single/|website=The Boot|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> It was a minor Top 40 hit on the country charts, peaking at number 36 on ''Billboard'' Country Airplay.\n\nIn October 2017, Cam announced a new single titled [[Diane (Cam song)|\"Diane\"]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/hear-cams-jolene-inspired-new-song-diane-w510372|title=Hear Cam's Supercharged, 'Jolene'-Inspired New Song 'Diane'|last=Betts|first=Stephen L.|date=October 27, 2017|work=Rolling Stone Country|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> She promoted the song with several live performances including on [[Good Morning America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countryliving.com/life/entertainment/a19681578/cam-diane-song/|title=Watch Dolly Parton Surprise Country Singer Cam On 'Good Morning America'|last=Matthews|first=Lauren|date=4 April 2018|work=Country Living|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8343549/late-late-show-cam-diane|title=Cam Gives Mesmerizing Performance of 'Diane' on 'The Late Late Show'|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=17 April 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> and as a duet with a contestant on [[American Idol (season 16)|season 16 of ''American Idol'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboot.com/cam-american-idol-effie-passero-diane-shannon-ohara-burning-house/|title=Cam Duets with 'American Idol' Contestants on 'Diane,' 'Burning House'|last=Stefano|first=Angela|date=17 April 2018|work=The Boot|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In April 2018, \"Diane\" was added to the [[BBC Radio 2]] A-list and hit No. 1 on iTunes for 5 weeks. Also in 2017, Cam, along with [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and Tyler Johnson, co-wrote the song \"Palace\" for Smith's 2017 album ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'' and providing background vocals and guitar to the track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/cam-wrote-sam-smith-song-we-had-same-heartache/|title=Country Star Cam on Writing a Song for Sam Smith's New Album: We Had the 'Same Heartache'|last=Nelson|first=Jeff|date=3 November 2017|work=People|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The song saw international success and was highlighted in the Holiday \"Sway\" commercial for [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] which led to its reaching No. 1 on the Billboard Top TV Commercials Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8093860/sam-smith-palace-apple-ad-top-tv-commercials-chart-number-one|title=Sam Smith's 'Palace' Hits No. 1 on Top TV Commercials Chart for December|last=Zellner|first=Xander|date=11 January 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> The widespread embrace of \"Palace\" included much international success, specifically in [[Japan]], where Smith performed the song on multiple TV talk shows. Cam opened for Smith on the Summer US leg of his 2018 The Thrill Of It All Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-joins-sam-smiths-thrill-of-it-all-tour-629146/|title=Cam Joins Sam Smith's Thrill of It All Tour|last=Betts|first=Stephen L.|date=7 June 2018|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Cam has also shared the stage with [[Tim McGraw]] and [[Faith Hill]] on their [[Soul2Soul: The World Tour|Soul2Soul Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/tim-mcgraw-faith-hills-soul2soul-tour-taps-devin-dawson-caitlyn-smith-127866/|title=Tim McGraw, Faith Hill's Soul2Soul Tour Taps Devin Dawson, Caitlyn Smith|last=Parton|first=Chris|date=19 March 2018|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> as well as [[Harry Styles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/harry-styles-invited-cam-open-nashville-concert-better-than-hype/|title=Harry Styles Invited Country Star Cam to Open His Nashville Show: 'He's Even Better Than All the Hype'|last=Nelson|first=Jeff|date=29 September 2017|work=People|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Cam released a new single entitled \"Road to Happiness\", which did not chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-road-to-happiness/|title=Cam Ponders the Real Meaning of Joy in 'Road to Happiness'|last=Whitaker|first=Sterling|date=13 July 2018|work=Taste of Country|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In 2019, she provided vocals for [[Diplo]]'s song \"[[So Long (Diplo song)|So Long]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-cam-so-long-thomas-wesley-828677/|title=Song You Need to Know: Diplo and Cam, 'So Long'|last=Freeman|first=Jon|last2=Freeman|first2=Jon|date=2019-05-02|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In February 2020, she released the song \"Til There's Nothing Left\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-till-theres-nothing-left-952115/|title=Cam Addresses Sex and Swagger on New Song, 'Till There's Nothing Left'|last=Freeman|first=Jon|last2=Freeman|first2=Jon|date=2020-02-13|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nCam was exposed to classic country music at an early age from the time spent on her grandparents' ranch. They introduced her to the musical sounds of [[Patsy Cline]], [[Bonnie Raitt]] and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=BilboarWlecomccount/> She was largely influenced by the vocal phrasing of Cline and [[Ray Charles]]. She also developed an appreciation for the [[Dixie Chicks]] and the [[Indigo Girls]], commenting that she was \"so into those female harmonies\". She additionally cites [[Bob Dylan]], [[Joni Mitchell]], and [[Randy Newman]] as influences on her songwriting style.<ref name=\"Billboard Interview\"/> Although she has a variety of musical influences, Cam stated that country music is where she felt most connected to. In a 2015 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', she explained her reasoning: \"I grew up singing in a lot of different languages and a lot of world music choirs, so I have a lot of musical influences. But the songwriting structure of country music is the standard in my mind. ... That structure seems to feel the most homey to me.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Cam - 10 New Country Artists You Need to Know: Spring 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-new-country-artists-you-need-to-know-spring-2015-20150505/cam-20150505|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn September 2015, Cam became engaged to Adam Weaver, a business broker with First Choice Business Brokers in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Laura|title=Cam Shows Off New Bling|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cam-engaged/|website=Taste of Country|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, the couple married in a small ceremony in a California desert.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Danielle|title=See Cam's Stunning Wedding Album!|url=http://people.com/country/cam-wedding-album-marries-adam-weaver/|website=People|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> In December 2019, she gave birth to her first child, Lucy. Shortly after giving birth, Cam posted on social media that she was a \"breech at 39wks, a next-day c-section (ouch) & here we are... three of us now.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Iasimone |first1=Ashley |title=Cam Gives Birth to Baby Lucy Marvel: See the Photos |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8546960/cam-baby-birth-announcement |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nCam is a vocal advocate for music education and inclusion. She spoke on the psychology of music in her 2017 TEDx Talk at the University of Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/5-things-we-learned-from-cams-tedx-talk-193313/|title=5 Things We Learned From Cam's TEDx Talk|last=Parton|first=Chris|date=7 March 2017|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> Cam is on the [[Academy of Country Music]] (ACM) Board and was invited to join [[The Recording Academy]]'s Task Force on Diversity and Inclusion in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/recording-academy-names-diversity-and-inclusion-task-force-members/|title= Recording Academy Names Diversity And Inclusion Task Force Members|date=9 May 2018|work=Grammy.com|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In 2018, Cam joined the speaker list on [[Hello Sunshine (company)|Hello Sunshine]] x Together Live's touring event<ref>{{cite web|url=http://togetherlive.com/about/|title= Our Stories Travel|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Cam discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Heartforward]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Untamed (Cam album)|Untamed]]'' (2015)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Recipient/Nominated work\n!Association\n!Award\n!Result\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"| 2016\n|rowspan=\"4\"| \"[[Burning House]]\"\n|[[58th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\n|[[Best Country Solo Performance]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" {{Nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|title = Grammy Nominations 2016: See the Full List of Nominees{{!}} Billboard|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6785974/grammy-nominations-2016-full-list|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| [[Academy of Country Music|ACM Awards]]\n|Single Record of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\">{{cite web|title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 51st ACADEMY OF COUNTRY MUSIC AWARDS\u00ae|url=http://www.acmcountry.com/news?n_id=954|website=[[Academy of Country Music]]|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Song of the Year\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=The ACM Awards: Nominees|url=http://www.acmawards.com/nominees|website=[[Academy of Country Music]]|accessdate=20 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308114318/http://www.acmawards.com/nominees|archivedate=8 March 2016|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n|Video of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Cam\n|New Female Vocalist of the Year\n|<ref name=\"ACM\"/>\n|-\n| [[American Music Awards of 2016|American Music Awards]]\n| Favorite Female Country Artist\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=American Music Awards Nominations 2016: See Full List of Nominees |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/american-music-awards-nominations-2016-full-list-nominees/story?id=42647918 |website=[[ABC News]] |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[Burning House]]\"\n|rowspan=2|[[Country Music Association|CMA Awards]]\n|Song of the Year\n|<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web |title=Past Winners and Nominees: Cam |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=74N0Q6J56D7M6H5CF18CX651D87L666415F225642LQA5VC53SWVZ5R0B3BAH34V0P6POGRC1ZR2H0N1E6FTGBBCC5HNQ93B15U03IN30B6R2RQ14Y5BH4H45CD9650S |website=[[Country Music Association Awards]] |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Music Video of the Year\n|<ref name=\"CMA\"/>\n|-\n| 2017\n| Cam\n| ACM Awards\n| New Female Vocalist of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n'''Supporting act'''\n*Strait Vegas Tour (2017) with [[George Strait]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2016/11/17/george-strait-adds-8-more-vegas-tour-dates-to-2017-schedule/ | title=George Strait Adds 8 More Vegas Tour Dates to 2017 Schedule | work=Nash Country Daily | date=November 17, 2016 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Somewhere on a Beach Tour]] (2016) with [[Dierks Bentley]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tasteofcountry.com/dierks-bentley-2016-somewhere-on-a-beach-tour-dates/ | title=Dierks Bentley announces 2016 Somewhere on a Beach Tour | publisher=[[Taste of Country]] | date=January 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Headlining'''\n* The Burning House Tour (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/cam-plots-headlining-burning-house-tour-w436831|title=Cam Plots Headlining Burning House Tour|first=Stephen L.|last=Betts|date=29 August 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* Best Coast Tour (2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/cam-announces-2017-best-coast-tour-w506118|title=Cam Unveils 2017 Best Coast Tour of California, Pacific Northwest|first=Brittney|last=McKenna|date=28 September 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* Listening Room Series (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/cam-plots-stripped-down-listening-room-series-tour-117086/|title= Cam Plots Stripped-Down \u2018Listening Room Series\u2019 Tour|first=Jon|last=Freeman|date=13 March 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n* \"Diane\" European Tour (2018)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/CAM-Announces-2019-Summer-European-Tour-20190603 | title=CAM Announces 2019 Summer European Tour | work=Broadway World | date=June 3, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n* Oh the Places We'll Go Tour (2019)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.antimusic.com/news/19/June/04Cam_Announces_The_Oh,_The_Places_Well_Go_Summer_Tour.shtml | title=Cam Announces The Oh, The Places We'll Go! Summer Tour | work=Anti Music | date=June 4, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.camcountry.com}}\n\n{{Cam}}\n\n{{auth