{"title_page": "Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)", "text_new": "{{short description|Fourth series of Love Island}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number    = 4\n| image            = \n| country          = United Kingdom\n| network          = [[ITV2]]\n| first_aired      = {{Start date|2018|6|4|df=y}}\n| last_aired       = {{End date|2018|7|30|df=y}}\n| num_episodes     = 49\n}}\nThe fourth series of ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]'', a British [[dating show|dating reality show]], began on 4 June 2018 on [[ITV2]], and concluded on 30 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a861866/love-island-final-2018-date/|title=The Love Island final date has been revealed|date=18 July 2018|work=Digital Spy}}</ref> It is the fourth from the current [[Love Island (2015 TV series)|revived series]], but sixth overall. [[Caroline Flack]] presented the series, while [[Iain Stirling]] narrated it. The series opener received the highest rating on a digital TV programme since the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] were broadcast on [[BBC Three]]; it was also the most watched programme ever on ITV2.\n\nOn 30 July 2018, the series was won by Dani Dyer and Jack Fincham having received 79.66% of the final vote, making this the biggest winning percentage since the show began.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/love-island-voting-figures-reveal-13009267|title=Love Island voting figures reveal exactly how much Dani and Jack won by|first=Vicki|last=Newman|date=31 July 2018|work=Daily Mirror}}</ref> Laura Anderson and Paul Knops finished as runners-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a862765/love-island-2018-winners/|title=The Love Island 2018 winners are...|date=30 July 2018|work=Digital Spy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44943562|title=Love Island: Dani Dyer and Jack Fincham win ITV2 series|date=31 July 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> The average viewers for this series was 3.96 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-10/|title=Weekly top 10 programmes|publisher=BARB}}</ref> up 1.44 million on the previous series.\n\nOn 11th January 2020, Irish TV Channel [[Virgin Media Two]] announced it would be re-airing this series due to popular demand. The 'Weekly Hotlist' or 'Aftersun' episodes are not being aired, however. <ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-xdO-ZKxma/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link</ref>\n\n==Production==\nDuring the final of the [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 3)|previous series]] on 24 July 2017, it was confirmed that ''Love Island'' would return for a fourth series due to air the following year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Duncan |first1=Amy |title=Love Island series 4 confirmed \u2013 but we have to wait a whole year for it |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/07/24/love-island-series-4-confirmed-but-we-have-to-wait-a-whole-year-for-it-6803071/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=24 July 2017}}</ref> It becomes the fourth series from the current [[Love Island (2015 TV series)|revived format]], but sixth series overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a641877/caroline-flack-confirmed-to-present-new-look-love-island-on-itv2/|title=Caroline Flack fronts new-look Love Island|last=Rigby|first=Sam|date=15 April 2015|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=4 July 2017}}</ref> [[Caroline Flack]] and [[Iain Stirling]] were confirmed to continue their roles as presenter and narrator, respectively.<ref name=\"Agius\">{{cite news |last1=Agius |first1=Nicola |last2=Guiltenane |first2=Christian |title=Love Island 2018: When it starts, line-up and everything else you need to know |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/feature/a847317/love-island-2018-cast-date-contestants/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=23 May 2018}}</ref> The first 10-second teaser for the new series began airing on 21 April 2018 with a second teaser released on 29 April.<ref name=\"Trailer\">{{cite news |last1=Houghton |first1=Rianne |title=Updated: Love Island 2018 is officially almost here as ITV2 drops another teaser |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a855349/love-island-start-date-2018-itv2-first-teaser-trailer/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=29 April 2018}}</ref> A full length trailer was released on 17 May, which Stephanie Chase of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' pointed out included \"all our favourite lingo from the show\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chase |first1=Stephanie |title=Love Island series 4's latest trailer includes every possible reference to show's cheeky lingo |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a857314/love-island-series-four-trailer-lingo/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=17 May 2018}}</ref> On 23 May, it was confirmed that the series would begin on 4 June on [[ITV2]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCreesh |first1=Louise |title=Love Island 2018 bags an official launch date, and it's really soon |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a857857/love-island-2018-start-date-itv2-launch-premiere/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=23 May 2018}}</ref> On 27 May, it was announced that a new spin-off, \"''Love Island: The Morning After''\", had been commissioned for the series. It is hosted by [[Kem Cetinay]] and Arielle Free and is a daily podcast delivering the freshest gossip to the fans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Houghton |first1=Rianne |title=Love Island star Kem Cetinay is presenting a new podcast about the show |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a858124/love-island-season-4-kem-cetinay-podcast-host/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=27 May 2018}}</ref> First look pictures of the villa were released on 31 May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harman |first1=Abi |title=Love Island 2018: First look at the lush new villa |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/reality-tv/news/g25271/love-island-2018-first-look-at-the-new-villa/?slide=8 |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=31 May 2018}}</ref> The sixteenth episode of the series, first broadcast on 21 June 2018, features a tribute to [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 2)|series 2]] contestant [[Sophie Gradon]], who died on 20 June.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harp |first1=Justin |title=Love Island pays on-air tribute to Sophie Gradon hours after her tragic death |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/love-island/news/a860016/love-island-tribute-sophie-gradon-after-death/ |accessdate=21 June 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome episodes this series were aired outside of the usual 9pm timeslot due to the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]].<ref>https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a21983893/love-island-time-change-teaser/</ref>\n\n==Islanders==\nAngela Jain, the managing director at ITV Studios Entertainment, wanted the series to feature \"some surprising cast members\", who the audience would not expect to see.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Frances |title=Love Island producers tease \"genuinely surprising\" cast for 2018 series |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-05-25/love-island-producers-tease-genuinely-surprising-cast-for-2018-series/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> She explained that she wanted \"enough cast that feels like they are absolutely heart and soul ''Love Island'' \u2013 and then a certain percentage of people who feel genuinely new to telly and genuinely surprising.\"<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> When asked whether a former contestant could appear in this series, executive producer Andy Cadman did not rule out anything, but said he struggled to imagine it.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrison |first1=Ellie |title=Could Love Island put a 2017 contestant back in the villa? |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2018-06-01/could-love-island-put-a-2017-contestant-back-in-the-villa/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=1 June 2018}}</ref> The first Islanders for the fourth series were released on 28 May 2018, just one week before the launch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Frances |title=Who's going to be in the new series of Love Island? |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-06-02/love-island-2018-cast-contestants-list-and-rumours-full-confirmed-line-up-revealed/ |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=2 June 2018}}</ref> However, throughout the series, more Islanders entered the villa to find love.<ref name=\"Harp\"/> Niall Aslam's decision to leave the series voluntarily for \"personal reasons\" marks the first time since the [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 2)|second series]] where an Islander voluntarily left the show.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44457713|title=Niall quits the Love Island villa|date=12 June 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref> The series was won by Dani Dyer and Jack Fincham having received 79.66% of the final vote.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=\"150\"|'''Islander'''\n! width=\"50\"|'''Age'''\n! width=\"120\"|'''Hometown'''\n! width=\"50\"|'''Entered'''\n! width=\"150\"|'''Status'''\n! width=\"50\"|'''{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''Dani Dyer'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''21'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[London]]'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''Day 1'''\n| style=\"background:gold;\"| '''Winner (Day 59)'''\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Waring|first1=Olivia|title