{"title_page": "Custody of the Holy Land", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Custody of the Holy Land\n| native_name         = {{lang-la|Custodia Terr\u00e6 Sanct\u00e6}}\n| native_name_lang    = [[Latin]]\n| named_after=\n| image               = Coat_of_arms_of_the_Custodian_of_the_Holy_Land.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| alt=\n| caption             = [[Coat of arms]] of the Custody of the Holy Land\n| map                 = \n| map_size=\n| map_alt=\n| map_caption=\n| map2=\n| map2_size=\n| map2_alt=\n| map2_caption=\n| abbreviation=\n| motto=\n| predecessor=\n| merged=\n| successor=\n| formation           = {{start date|1217|df=y}}\n| founder             = [[Saint Francis of Assisi]]\n| founding_location   = [[Porziuncola]], [[Assisi]], [[Umbria]]\n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger=\n| type=\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status=\n| purpose             = \"The grace of the [[Holy Places at Jerusalem|Holy Places]]\"\n| headquarters        = [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]]\n| location            = [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old city of Jerusalem]]\n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} 36.8264467,23.8663976,5z  =-->\n| region              = [[Holy Land]]; [[Middle East]]\n| services            = [[Fathers of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n| products=\n| methods=\n| fields=\n| membership=\n| membership_year=\n| language=\n| owner               = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| sec_gen=\n| leader_title        = [[Custos (Franciscans)|Custos]]\n| leader_name         = Father [[Francesco Patton]]\n| leader_title2       = [[Vicar|Custodial Vicar]]\n| leader_name2        = Father [[Dobromir Jasztal]]\n| leader_title3       = [[General Secretary]]\n| leader_name3        = Father [[Marco Carrara]]\n| leader_title4=\n| leader_name4=\n| board_of_directors=\n| key_people=\n| main_organ=\n| parent_organization = [[Order of Friars Minor]]\n| subsidiaries=\n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem|Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]]<br>[[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n| slogan              = \n| mission=\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.custodia.org/}}\n| remarks=\n| formerly=\n| footnotes=\n}}\n\nThe '''Custody of the Holy Land''' ([[Latin]]: ''Custodia Terr\u00e6 Sanct\u00e6'') is a [[Custos (Franciscans)|custodian]] [[priory]] of the [[Order of Friars Minor]] in [[Jerusalem]], founded as ''Province of the Holy Land'' in 1217 by [[Saint Francis of Assisi]], who also founded the Franciscan Order. Its mission is to [[:wikt:guard|guard]] \"the grace of the [[Holy Places at Jerusalem|Holy Places]]\" of the [[Holy Land]] and the rest of the [[Middle East]], \"sanctified by the presence of [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus]]\",<ref>{{cite web |author= John Abela |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/san/TSsanct.html |title=Christian Sanctuaries in the Holy Land |publisher= Christusrex.org |date= 2001-12-18 |access-date=2015-12-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221938/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/san/TSsanct.html |archive-date= 2015-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as [[pilgrim]]s visiting them, on behalf of the [[Catholic Church]].<ref name=\"Role\">{{cite web |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TScustos.html |title= The role of the Custos for the Holy Land |publisher= Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160306193814/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TScustos.html |archive-date= 2016-03-06|url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=HistoryCHL>{{cite web |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TShistry.html |title= The role of the Custos for the Holy Land |publisher= Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |access-date= 8 April 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150923203202/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TShistry.html |archive-date= 23 September 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 1342, the Franciscans were declared by two [[papal bull]]s as the official custodians of the Holy Places in the name of the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Bull1342\"/>\n\nThe Custody [[headquarter]]s are located in the [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]], a 16th-century Franciscan [[monastery]] near the [[New Gate]] in the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City of Jerusalem]]. The office can bestow\u2014only to those entering its office\u2014the [[Jerusalem Pilgrim's Cross]] upon deserving Catholic visitors to the city.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Franciscans trace their presence in the Holy Land to 1217. By 1229, the friars had a small house near the [[fifth station]] of the [[Via Dolorosa]] and in 1272 were permitted to settle in the [[Cenacle]] on [[Mount Zion]]. In 1309 they also settled in [[Bethlehem]] and the [[Holy Sepulchre]] along with the [[Canons Regular of the Holy Sepulchre|Canons Regular]].\n\nAfter the final [[Fall of Acre|fall]] of the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem#The Kingdom of Acre|second Crusader Kingdom of Jerusalem]] in 1291, the title of [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]] was vested in the Custody ''[[ex officio]]'' in [[Rome]], while resuming its activities in the Holy Land, including surveilling the [[accolade]]s of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]] 1342-1489 until its [[Grand Master (order)|Grand Magistry]] was vested in the [[papacy]]. Following the restoration of the [[Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] as residential [[episcopal see]] in 1847, the Patriarch henceforth additionally assumed the position of the order's ecclesiastical superior, eventually supplanting the Custody of the Holy land as [[Grand Prior]] of the Order of the Holy Sepulchre.\n\nThe Custody of the Holy Land has repeatedly expressed concern about the survival of the [[Holy Land#Christianity|Christians in the Holy Land]], including the strained situation for [[Christianity in the Middle East|Christians in the rest of the Middle East]].<ref name=\"catholicnews1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110827065317/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1103383.htm Middle East Christians must be courageous, open, says Franciscan custos]</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2016, the ''Custodial [[Curia]]'' was led by ''[[Custos (Franciscans)|Custos]]'' Fr. [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa]].<ref name=Admin/><ref name=Challenge>{{cite web |url= http://www.zenit.org/en/articles/challenges-of-new-franciscan-custodian-of-holy-land |title= Challenges of New Franciscan Custodian of Holy Land: Interview With Father Pierbattista Pizzaballa |publisher= ZENIT |date=24 May 2004 |access-date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> Since 2016, the chief custodian has been [[Francesco Patton]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:StFrancis part.jpg|thumb|Oldest known portrait in existence of the saint who founded the Order of Friars Minor and its Custody of the Holy Land, dating back to Saint Francis' retreat to [[Subiaco, Lazio|Subiaco]] (1223\u20131224); depicted without the [[stigmata]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paradoxplace.com/Perspectives/Rome%20&%20Central%20Italy/Subiaco/Subiaco.htm|title=Italy/Subiaco|publisher=www.paradoxplace.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113034105/http://www.paradoxplace.com/Perspectives/Rome%20%26%20Central%20Italy/Subiaco/Subiaco.htm|archive-date=2015-01-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>]] \nAn online history, [http://www.custodia.org/IMG/pdf/The_Franciscan_presence_in_the_Holy_Land.pdf The Franciscan Presence in the Holy Land]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, has been prepared by the Custodian Emeritus, [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa|Archbishop Pierbattista Pizzaballa, OFM]].\n\nThe Franciscan presence in the Holy Land started in 1217, when the province of [[Syria]] was established, with Frater (Brother) [[Elias of Cortona]] as [[Minister (Christianity)|Minister]]. By 1229, the friars had a small house near the [[fifth station]] of the [[Via Dolorosa]]. In 1272 the [[Sultan]] [[Baibars]] of [[Egypt]] permitted the Franciscans to settle in the [[Cenacle]] (also called the Upper Room) on [[Mount Zion|Mount Sion]]. Later on, in 1309, they also settled in [[Bethlehem]] and in the [[Holy Sepulchre]], along with the [[Canons Regular of the Holy Sepulchre|Canons Regular]].\n\n[[File:Giotto - Legend of St Francis - -11- - St Francis before the Sultan (Trial by Fire).jpg|thumb|Saint Francis before [[Sultan]] [[Al-Kamil]] of [[Egypt]], witnessing the trial by fire (wall [[fresco]], [[Giotto]])]]\nIn 1333, [[Robert, King of Naples|Robert d'Anjou]], [[Kingdom of Naples|King of Naples]], and his wife, [[Sancia of Majorca]], bought the Cenacle from the Sultan of Egypt and gave it to the Franciscans. In 1342, [[Pope Clement VI]], by the [[Papal bull]]s ''[[List of papal bulls|Gratiam agimus]]'' and ''[[Nuper charissimae]]'' declared the Franciscans as the official custodians of the Holy Places in the name of the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Bull1342\">[http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSbulla_En. The Bull of Clement VI (1342)]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A portion reads:\n\n<blockquote>\nA short time ago good news from the king and queen reached our Apostolic See relating that, at great cost and following difficult negotiations, they had obtained a concession from the Sultan of Babylon [that is, Cairo], who to the intense shame of Christians occupies the Holy Sepulchre of the Lord and the other Holy Places beyond the sea that were sanctified by the blood of this same Redeemer, to wit that friars of your Order may reside continuously in the church known as the Sepulchre and celebrate there Solemn Sung Masses and the Divine Office in the manner of the several friars of this Order who are already present in this place; moreover, this same Sultan has also conceded to the King and Queen the Cenacle of the Lord, the chapel where the Holy Spirit was manifested to the Apostles and the other chapel in which Christ appeared to the Apostles after his resurrection, in the presence of Blessed Thomas; and also the news of how the Queen built a convent on Mount Zion where, as is known, the Cenacle and the said chapels are located; where for some time she has had the intention of supporting twelve friars of your Order to assure the divine Liturgy in the church of the Holy Sepulchre, along with three laymen charged with serving the friars and seeing to their needs.<ref>[http://www.custodia.org/IMG/pdf/The_Franciscan_presence_in_the_Holy_Land.pdf ''The Franciscan Presence in the Holy Land,'' by Fr. Pierbattista Pizzaballa, OFM, Franciscan Printing Press - Jerusalem 2008]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n[[File:ChurchOfTheHolySepulcher1885.png|thumb|[[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] (1885). Other than some restoration work, its appearance has essentially not changed since 1854. The [[Immovable Ladder]], the small ladder below the top-right window, is also visible in recent photographs; this has remained in the same position since 1754 over a disagreement to remove it.]]\nThe Custodian was described as the \"Guardian of Mount Zion in Jerusalem\". Between 1342 and 1489, the Custodian was the head of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]] and held the ''ex officio'' title of [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]]. From 1374, he was based at the [[Basilica di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]] in [[Rome]].\n\nIn 1489, Pope [[Innocent VIII]] suppressed the Order of the Holy Sepulchre and ruled that it was to be merged with the [[Knights Hospitaller]]. In 1496, Pope [[Alexander VI]], restored the Order of Holy Sepulchre to independent status, but the Custodian ceased to be the head of the Order. Instead, a [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|Grand Master of the Order]] was created, and the office vested in the papacy. The Custodian continued to act as the Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem ''ex officio'' until 1830, and by being appointed to both offices until 1905. The office of Grand Master remained vested in the papacy until 1949.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist1.html |title= Official website page 1 |access-date= 2009-08-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151250/http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist1.html |archive-date= 2015-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 29 August 2011, Archbishop [[Edwin Frederick O'Brien]] was appointed by [[Pope Benedict XVI]] Grand Master to succeed Cardinal [[John Patrick Foley]], who resigned the office on 24 February 2011 due to ill health. The Order is a member of many international bodies and has observer status at others (such as the [[United Nations]]). The Grand Master is a papal [[viceroy]] who assists Vatican diplomacy with procedural support for making motions, proposing amendments and requiring votes in the sphere of international diplomacy.\n\n[[Franciscan]] friars cared for the Cenacle, restoring also the building with [[gothic architecture|Gothic]] vaults, until 1552 when the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]] captured Jerusalem and banished all Christians. After the Franciscan friars' eviction, the Cenacle was transformed into a [[mosque]]. Christians were not allowed to use the room for prayer until the establishment of the State of [[Israel]] in 1948.\n\nIn 1623, the Latin Province of the Holy Land was split into a number of smaller entities, called Custodies - creating Custodies of Cyprus, Syria, and the Holy Land proper. The Custody of the Holy Land included the monasteries of [[Saint-Jean-d'Acre]], [[Antioch]], [[Sidon]], [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], [[Jerusalem]] and [[Jaffa]].\n\nIn 1847, a resident Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem was restored in the Holy Land, together with the Order of the Holy Sepulchre. The Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem became the ecclesiastical superior of the Order, and eventually assumed the title Grand Prior, supplanting the Custodian. The office of Grand Master still remained vested in the papacy.\n\nIn 1937, [[Alberto Gori]] was appointed Custodian of the Holy Land, an office he would occupy until 1949, when he was appointed Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem, an office he held until 1970. In Gori's reports to the Vatican in the 1940s, he was critical of Jewish and later Israeli forces, whom he accused of destruction of holy places.<ref name=\"gori\"/> Despite repeated Israeli assurances that Israel will guarantee [[freedom of religion]] and safeguard the Holy Places of all religions, Pope [[Pius XII]] issued several encyclicals expressing concerns about the holy places as well as access.<ref>E.g., ''[[Auspicia quaedam]]'' of 1 May 1948, two weeks before the end of the British Mandate; ''[[In multiplicibus curis]]'' on 24 October 1948; and ''[[Redemptoris nostri cruciatus]]'' of 15 April 1949.</ref> In 1949, at the time of appointing Gori to the office of Latin Patriarch, Pius XII also relinquished the title of Grand Master.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist2.html |title=Official website page 2 |access-date=2009-08-05 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914155712/http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist2.html |archive-date=2012-09-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:Catholic monks in Jerusalem 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Franciscan]] [[monks]] during the [[procession]] on the [[Calvary]] in the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]](2006).]]\n\nOn 15 May 2004, Fr. Pierbattista Pizzaballa was appointed Custodian of the Holy Land,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/sbf/segr/ntz/foto2004/newcustos.html |title=Father Pierbattista Pizzaballa an SBF professor new Custos of the Holy Land |access-date=2009-08-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908041346/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/sbf/segr/ntz/foto2004/newcustos.html |archive-date=2008-09-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> succeeding [[Giovanni Battistelli]], who held the office for six years.<ref name=Admin>{{cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSadmin.html |title=Administration |publisher=Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923203200/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSadmin.html |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Challenge/> On Friday, June 28, 2013, [[Pope Francis]] confirmed that he would continue as Custodian for at least a further three years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://attualita.vatican.va/sala-stampa/bollettino/2013/06/28/news/31303.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701180525/http://attualita.vatican.va/sala-stampa/bollettino/2013/06/28/news/31303.html |archive-date=2013-07-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Pierbattista Pizzaballa was born in [[Cologno al Serio]], [[Italy]], on 21 April 1965. He was ordained a priest in September 1990. Since 2016, the chief custodian has been [[Francesco Patton]].\n\nThe Custodian of the Holy Land, also called the International Custodian of the Holy Land, is appointed by the General Definitorium of the [[Order of Friars Minor]] (OFM) of the Franciscans and approved by the [[Pope]] and the [[Holy See]].<ref name=Challenge/>\n\nThe Custodian has the role of Minister Provincial (i.e. major superior) of the [[Franciscan]]s living in [[Israel]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Jordan]], [[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], parts of [[Egypt]], [[Cyprus]] and [[Rhodes]]. The Custody has about 300 friars and about 100 sisters in these countries. The Franciscans serve the principal Christian shrines, including the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in [[Jerusalem]], [[Basilica of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]] and the [[Basilica of the Annunciation]] in [[Nazareth]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/senior-catholic-cleric-if-jews-want-respect-they-must-respect-others.premium-1.463320 Hareetz: \"Senior Catholic cleric: 'If Jews want respect, they must respect others'\" By Nir Hasson] September 07, 2012</ref>\n\nDuring the later Middle Ages and early modern times the Custody was official provider of hospitality for Latin pilgrims to the Holy Land, i.e. Westerners be they Catholic or Protestant. Such facilities existed primarily at [[Jaffa]] and in Jerusalem\n\n===Properties in the Holy Land===\n[[File:St._Saviour_Church_(Jerusalem).jpg|thumb|The church of the [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]] in [[Jerusalem]].]] \nThe Franciscan order owns a great deal of property in the Holy Land, second only to the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Orthodox Church of Jerusalem]]. In addition to the major shrines of the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in Jerusalem and the [[Basilica of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]], which the Franciscans [[Status quo (Holy Land sites)|own and administer in common]] with the Jerusalem Orthodox and [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem|Armenian Orthodox]] patriarchates, the Custodian also cares for 74 shrines and sanctuaries throughout the Holy Land, including properties in Syria and Jordan.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/104083146.html?dids=104083146:104083146&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jan+25%2C+2002&author=Patricia+Golan&pub=Jerusalem+Post&edition=&startpage=32&desc=The+gatekeeper Jerusalem Post Jan 25, 2002 - The gatekeeper]</ref>\n\nIn 1909, in the territory of the [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem|Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]], re-instituted in 1847, the Franciscans had 24 convents and 15 parishes, including numerous schools.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06281a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]</ref>\n\nThe Custodian's offices are at the [[Monastery of St Saviour]], a 16th-century Franciscan monastery near [[New Gate]] in the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City of Jerusalem]].\n\n== Activities ==\n\n===Education===\nSchools founded by the Franciscan friars include [[Terra Santa College]] in Nicosia, Cyprus and \nMagnificat Institute in Jerusalem.\n\n===Current issues===\n[[File:Palestinian Christian Scouts Nativity Church in Bethlehem Christmas Eve 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Palestinian Christian]] [[scouts]] on [[Christmas Eve]] in front of the [[Church of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]] (2006).]]\nFr. Pizzaballa expressed concern view that many Christians were leaving the region, especially the [[Palestinian Christians|Christians of the Palestinian Territories]], and that housing assistance was being offered to discourage [[emigration]]. He attributed the exodus to lack of prospects for the future and the political situation.<ref name=Challenge/>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Catholic News Service]] (CNS) website aired an interview on [[Vatican Radio]] in which Father Pizzaballa alluded to the tense situation for Christians in Syria and Egypt.<ref name=\"catholicnews1\"/>\n\n==List of Custodians==\n\n{{Expand list|date=September 2016}}\n* Giuseppe Baldi (1894)\n* Roberto Razz\u00f2li (1906-1912)<ref name=gori>[http://www.terrasanta.net/tsx/assets/pdf/GoriVersioMaiorENG.pdf Paolo Pieraccini, Custos of the Holy Land and Patriarch at the Second Vatican Council]</ref>\n* Ferdinando Diotallevi (1917-1924)<ref name=gori />\n* Aurelio Marotta (1925-1931)<ref name=gori />\n* Nazareno Iacopozzi (1931-1937)<ref name=gori />\n* [[Alberto Gori]] (1937-1949)<ref name=gori />\n* [[Carlo Ceccitelli]] (1986-1992)\n* [[Giuseppe Nazzaro]] (1992-1998)\n* [[Giovanni Battistelli]] (1998-2004)\n* [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa]] (2004\u20132016)\n* [[Francesco Patton]] (2016\u2013)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]]\n* [[Catholic Church in Palestine]]\n* [[Catholic Church in Israel]]\n* [[Palestinian Christians]]\n* [[Holy See\u2013Israel relations]]\n* [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n* [[Brotherhood of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n* [[ATS Association of the Holy Land]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00263206.2012.653139 Masha Halevi, Between Faith and Science: Franciscan Archaeology in the Service of the Holy Places, Middle Eastern Studies, Volume 48, Issue 2, 2012, pp. 249-267]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090106065146/http://custodia.org/ Official website of the Custody of the Holy Land]\n{{Franciscans}}\n{{Francis of Assisi|state=collapsed}}\n{{Old City (Jerusalem)}}\n\n{{coord|31.7791|N|35.2275|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Custody of the Holy Land| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Custody of the Holy Land\n| native_name         = {{lang-la|Custodia Terr\u00e6 Sanct\u00e6}}\n| native_name_lang    = [[Latin]]\n| named_after=\n| image               = Coat_of_arms_of_the_Custodian_of_the_Holy_Land.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| alt=\n| caption             = [[Coat of arms]] of the Custody of the Holy Land\n| map                 = \n| map_size=\n| map_alt=\n| map_caption=\n| map2=\n| map2_size=\n| map2_alt=\n| map2_caption=\n| abbreviation=\n| motto=\n| predecessor=\n| merged=\n| successor=\n| formation           = {{start date|1217|df=y}}\n| founder             = [[Saint Francis of Assisi]]\n| founding_location   = [[Porziuncola]], [[Assisi]], [[Umbria]]\n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger=\n| type=\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status=\n| purpose             = \"The grace of the [[Holy Places at Jerusalem|Holy Places]]\"\n| headquarters        = [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]]\n| location            = [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old city of Jerusalem]]\n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} 36.8264467,23.8663976,5z  =-->\n| region              = [[Holy Land]]; [[Middle East]]\n| services            = [[Fathers of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n| products=\n| methods=\n| fields=\n| membership=\n| membership_year=\n| language=\n| owner               = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| sec_gen=\n| leader_title        = [[Custos (Franciscans)|Custos]]\n| leader_name         = Father [[Francesco Patton]]\n| leader_title2       = [[Vicar|Custodial Vicar]]\n| leader_name2        = Father [[Dobromir Jasztal]]\n| leader_title3       = [[General Secretary]]\n| leader_name3        = Father [[Marco Carrara]]\n| leader_title4=\n| leader_name4=\n| board_of_directors=\n| key_people=\n| main_organ=\n| parent_organization = [[Order of Friars Minor]]\n| subsidiaries=\n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem|Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]]<br>[[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n| slogan              = \n| mission=\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.custodia.org/}}\n| remarks=\n| formerly=\n| footnotes=\n}}\n\nThe '''Custody of the Holy Land''' ([[Latin]]: ''Custodia Terr\u00e6 Sanct\u00e6'') is a [[Custos (Franciscans)|custodian]] [[priory]] of the [[Franciscan order]] in [[Jerusalem]], founded as ''Province of the Holy Land'' in 1217 by [[Saint Francis of Assisi]], who also founded the Franciscan Order. Its mission is to [[:wikt:guard|guard]] \"the grace of the [[Holy Places at Jerusalem|Holy Places]]\" of the [[Holy Land]] and the rest of the [[Middle East]], \"sanctified by the presence of [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus]]\",<ref>{{cite web |author= John Abela |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/san/TSsanct.html |title=Christian Sanctuaries in the Holy Land |publisher= Christusrex.org |date= 2001-12-18 |access-date=2015-12-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221938/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/san/TSsanct.html |archive-date= 2015-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as [[pilgrim]]s visiting them, on behalf of the [[Catholic Church]].<ref name=\"Role\">{{cite web |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TScustos.html |title= The role of the Custos for the Holy Land |publisher= Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160306193814/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TScustos.html |archive-date= 2016-03-06|url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=HistoryCHL>{{cite web |url= http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TShistry.html |title= The role of the Custos for the Holy Land |publisher= Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |access-date= 8 April 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150923203202/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TShistry.html |archive-date= 23 September 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 1342, the Franciscans were declared by two [[papal bull]]s as the official custodians of the Holy Places in the name of the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Bull1342\"/>\n\nThe Custody [[headquarter]]s are located in the [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]], a 16th-century Franciscan [[monastery]] near the [[New Gate]] in the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City of Jerusalem]]. The office can bestow\u2014only to those entering its office\u2014the [[Jerusalem Pilgrim's Cross]] upon deserving Catholic visitors to the city.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Franciscans trace their presence in the Holy Land to 1217. By 1229, the friars had a small house near the [[fifth station]] of the [[Via Dolorosa]] and in 1272 were permitted to settle in the [[Cenacle]] on [[Mount Zion]]. In 1309 they also settled in [[Bethlehem]] and the [[Holy Sepulchre]] along with the [[Canons Regular of the Holy Sepulchre|Canons Regular]].\n\nAfter the final [[Fall of Acre|fall]] of the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem#The Kingdom of Acre|second Crusader Kingdom of Jerusalem]] in 1291, the title of [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]] was vested in the Custody ''[[ex officio]]'' in [[Rome]], while resuming its activities in the Holy Land, including surveilling the [[accolade]]s of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]] 1342-1489 until its [[Grand Master (order)|Grand Magistry]] was vested in the [[papacy]]. Following the restoration of the [[Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] as residential [[episcopal see]] in 1847, the Patriarch henceforth additionally assumed the position of the order's ecclesiastical superior, eventually supplanting the Custody of the Holy land as [[Grand Prior]] of the Order of the Holy Sepulchre.\n\nThe Custody of the Holy Land has repeatedly expressed concern about the survival of the [[Holy Land#Christianity|Christians in the Holy Land]], including the strained situation for [[Christianity in the Middle East|Christians in the rest of the Middle East]].<ref name=\"catholicnews1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110827065317/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1103383.htm Middle East Christians must be courageous, open, says Franciscan custos]</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2016, the ''Custodial [[Curia]]'' was led by ''[[Custos (Franciscans)|Custos]]'' Fr. [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa]].<ref name=Admin/><ref name=Challenge>{{cite web |url= http://www.zenit.org/en/articles/challenges-of-new-franciscan-custodian-of-holy-land |title= Challenges of New Franciscan Custodian of Holy Land: Interview With Father Pierbattista Pizzaballa |publisher= ZENIT |date=24 May 2004 |access-date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> Since 2016, the chief custodian has been [[Francesco Patton]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:StFrancis part.jpg|thumb|Oldest known portrait in existence of the saint who founded the Order of Friars Minor and its Custody of the Holy Land, dating back to Saint Francis' retreat to [[Subiaco, Lazio|Subiaco]] (1223\u20131224); depicted without the [[stigmata]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paradoxplace.com/Perspectives/Rome%20&%20Central%20Italy/Subiaco/Subiaco.htm|title=Italy/Subiaco|publisher=www.paradoxplace.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113034105/http://www.paradoxplace.com/Perspectives/Rome%20%26%20Central%20Italy/Subiaco/Subiaco.htm|archive-date=2015-01-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>]] \nAn online history, [http://www.custodia.org/IMG/pdf/The_Franciscan_presence_in_the_Holy_Land.pdf The Franciscan Presence in the Holy Land]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, has been prepared by the Custodian Emeritus, [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa|Archbishop Pierbattista Pizzaballa, OFM]].\n\nThe Franciscan presence in the Holy Land started in 1217, when the province of [[Syria]] was established, with Frater (Brother) [[Elias of Cortona]] as [[Minister (Christianity)|Minister]]. By 1229, the friars had a small house near the [[fifth station]] of the [[Via Dolorosa]]. In 1272 the [[Sultan]] [[Baibars]] of [[Egypt]] permitted the Franciscans to settle in the [[Cenacle]] (also called the Upper Room) on [[Mount Zion|Mount Sion]]. Later on, in 1309, they also settled in [[Bethlehem]] and in the [[Holy Sepulchre]], along with the [[Canons Regular of the Holy Sepulchre|Canons Regular]].\n\n[[File:Giotto - Legend of St Francis - -11- - St Francis before the Sultan (Trial by Fire).jpg|thumb|Saint Francis before [[Sultan]] [[Al-Kamil]] of [[Egypt]], witnessing the trial by fire (wall [[fresco]], [[Giotto]])]]\nIn 1333, [[Robert, King of Naples|Robert d'Anjou]], [[Kingdom of Naples|King of Naples]], and his wife, [[Sancia of Majorca]], bought the Cenacle from the Sultan of Egypt and gave it to the Franciscans. In 1342, [[Pope Clement VI]], by the [[Papal bull]]s ''[[List of papal bulls|Gratiam agimus]]'' and ''[[Nuper charissimae]]'' declared the Franciscans as the official custodians of the Holy Places in the name of the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Bull1342\">[http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSbulla_En. The Bull of Clement VI (1342)]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A portion reads:\n\n<blockquote>\nA short time ago good news from the king and queen reached our Apostolic See relating that, at great cost and following difficult negotiations, they had obtained a concession from the Sultan of Babylon [that is, Cairo], who to the intense shame of Christians occupies the Holy Sepulchre of the Lord and the other Holy Places beyond the sea that were sanctified by the blood of this same Redeemer, to wit that friars of your Order may reside continuously in the church known as the Sepulchre and celebrate there Solemn Sung Masses and the Divine Office in the manner of the several friars of this Order who are already present in this place; moreover, this same Sultan has also conceded to the King and Queen the Cenacle of the Lord, the chapel where the Holy Spirit was manifested to the Apostles and the other chapel in which Christ appeared to the Apostles after his resurrection, in the presence of Blessed Thomas; and also the news of how the Queen built a convent on Mount Zion where, as is known, the Cenacle and the said chapels are located; where for some time she has had the intention of supporting twelve friars of your Order to assure the divine Liturgy in the church of the Holy Sepulchre, along with three laymen charged with serving the friars and seeing to their needs.<ref>[http://www.custodia.org/IMG/pdf/The_Franciscan_presence_in_the_Holy_Land.pdf ''The Franciscan Presence in the Holy Land,'' by Fr. Pierbattista Pizzaballa, OFM, Franciscan Printing Press - Jerusalem 2008]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n[[File:ChurchOfTheHolySepulcher1885.png|thumb|[[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] (1885). Other than some restoration work, its appearance has essentially not changed since 1854. The [[Immovable Ladder]], the small ladder below the top-right window, is also visible in recent photographs; this has remained in the same position since 1754 over a disagreement to remove it.]]\nThe Custodian was described as the \"Guardian of Mount Zion in Jerusalem\". Between 1342 and 1489, the Custodian was the head of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]] and held the ''ex officio'' title of [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]]. From 1374, he was based at the [[Basilica di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]] in [[Rome]].\n\nIn 1489, Pope [[Innocent VIII]] suppressed the Order of the Holy Sepulchre and ruled that it was to be merged with the [[Knights Hospitaller]]. In 1496, Pope [[Alexander VI]], restored the Order of Holy Sepulchre to independent status, but the Custodian ceased to be the head of the Order. Instead, a [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|Grand Master of the Order]] was created, and the office vested in the papacy. The Custodian continued to act as the Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem ''ex officio'' until 1830, and by being appointed to both offices until 1905. The office of Grand Master remained vested in the papacy until 1949.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist1.html |title= Official website page 1 |access-date= 2009-08-05 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151250/http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist1.html |archive-date= 2015-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 29 August 2011, Archbishop [[Edwin Frederick O'Brien]] was appointed by [[Pope Benedict XVI]] Grand Master to succeed Cardinal [[John Patrick Foley]], who resigned the office on 24 February 2011 due to ill health. The Order is a member of many international bodies and has observer status at others (such as the [[United Nations]]). The Grand Master is a papal [[viceroy]] who assists Vatican diplomacy with procedural support for making motions, proposing amendments and requiring votes in the sphere of international diplomacy.\n\n[[Franciscan]] friars cared for the Cenacle, restoring also the building with [[gothic architecture|Gothic]] vaults, until 1552 when the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]] captured Jerusalem and banished all Christians. After the Franciscan friars' eviction, the Cenacle was transformed into a [[mosque]]. Christians were not allowed to use the room for prayer until the establishment of the State of [[Israel]] in 1948.\n\nIn 1623, the Latin Province of the Holy Land was split into a number of smaller entities, called Custodies - creating Custodies of Cyprus, Syria, and the Holy Land proper. The Custody of the Holy Land included the monasteries of [[Saint-Jean-d'Acre]], [[Antioch]], [[Sidon]], [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], [[Jerusalem]] and [[Jaffa]].\n\nIn 1847, a resident Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem was restored in the Holy Land, together with the Order of the Holy Sepulchre. The Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem became the ecclesiastical superior of the Order, and eventually assumed the title Grand Prior, supplanting the Custodian. The office of Grand Master still remained vested in the papacy.\n\nIn 1937, [[Alberto Gori]] was appointed Custodian of the Holy Land, an office he would occupy until 1949, when he was appointed Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem, an office he held until 1970. In Gori's reports to the Vatican in the 1940s, he was critical of Jewish and later Israeli forces, whom he accused of destruction of holy places.<ref name=\"gori\"/> Despite repeated Israeli assurances that Israel will guarantee [[freedom of religion]] and safeguard the Holy Places of all religions, Pope [[Pius XII]] issued several encyclicals expressing concerns about the holy places as well as access.<ref>E.g., ''[[Auspicia quaedam]]'' of 1 May 1948, two weeks before the end of the British Mandate; ''[[In multiplicibus curis]]'' on 24 October 1948; and ''[[Redemptoris nostri cruciatus]]'' of 15 April 1949.</ref> In 1949, at the time of appointing Gori to the office of Latin Patriarch, Pius XII also relinquished the title of Grand Master.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist2.html |title=Official website page 2 |access-date=2009-08-05 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914155712/http://www.order-of-the-holy-sepulchre.org/hist2.html |archive-date=2012-09-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:Catholic monks in Jerusalem 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Franciscan]] [[monks]] during the [[procession]] on the [[Calvary]] in the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]](2006).]]\n\nOn 15 May 2004, Fr. Pierbattista Pizzaballa was appointed Custodian of the Holy Land,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/sbf/segr/ntz/foto2004/newcustos.html |title=Father Pierbattista Pizzaballa an SBF professor new Custos of the Holy Land |access-date=2009-08-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908041346/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/sbf/segr/ntz/foto2004/newcustos.html |archive-date=2008-09-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> succeeding [[Giovanni Battistelli]], who held the office for six years.<ref name=Admin>{{cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSadmin.html |title=Administration |publisher=Franciscan Custody of the Holy Land |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923203200/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/cust/TSadmin.html |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Challenge/> On Friday, June 28, 2013, [[Pope Francis]] confirmed that he would continue as Custodian for at least a further three years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://attualita.vatican.va/sala-stampa/bollettino/2013/06/28/news/31303.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701180525/http://attualita.vatican.va/sala-stampa/bollettino/2013/06/28/news/31303.html |archive-date=2013-07-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Pierbattista Pizzaballa was born in [[Cologno al Serio]], [[Italy]], on 21 April 1965. He was ordained a priest in September 1990. Since 2016, the chief custodian has been [[Francesco Patton]].\n\nThe Custodian of the Holy Land, also called the International Custodian of the Holy Land, is appointed by the General Definitorium of the [[Order of Friars Minor]] (OFM) of the Franciscans and approved by the [[Pope]] and the [[Holy See]].<ref name=Challenge/>\n\nThe Custodian has the role of Minister Provincial (i.e. major superior) of the [[Franciscan]]s living in [[Israel]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Jordan]], [[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], parts of [[Egypt]], [[Cyprus]] and [[Rhodes]]. The Custody has about 300 friars and about 100 sisters in these countries. The Franciscans serve the principal Christian shrines, including the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in [[Jerusalem]], [[Basilica of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]] and the [[Basilica of the Annunciation]] in [[Nazareth]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/senior-catholic-cleric-if-jews-want-respect-they-must-respect-others.premium-1.463320 Hareetz: \"Senior Catholic cleric: 'If Jews want respect, they must respect others'\" By Nir Hasson] September 07, 2012</ref>\n\nDuring the later Middle Ages and early modern times the Custody was official provider of hospitality for Latin pilgrims to the Holy Land, i.e. Westerners be they Catholic or Protestant. Such facilities existed primarily at [[Jaffa]] and in Jerusalem\n\n===Properties in the Holy Land===\n[[File:St._Saviour_Church_(Jerusalem).jpg|thumb|The church of the [[Monastery of Saint Saviour]] in [[Jerusalem]].]] \nThe Franciscan order owns a great deal of property in the Holy Land, second only to the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Orthodox Church of Jerusalem]]. In addition to the major shrines of the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in Jerusalem and the [[Basilica of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]], which the Franciscans [[Status quo (Holy Land sites)|own and administer in common]] with the Jerusalem Orthodox and [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem|Armenian Orthodox]] patriarchates, the Custodian also cares for 74 shrines and sanctuaries throughout the Holy Land, including properties in Syria and Jordan.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/104083146.html?dids=104083146:104083146&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jan+25%2C+2002&author=Patricia+Golan&pub=Jerusalem+Post&edition=&startpage=32&desc=The+gatekeeper Jerusalem Post Jan 25, 2002 - The gatekeeper]</ref>\n\nIn 1909, in the territory of the [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem|Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]], re-instituted in 1847, the Franciscans had 24 convents and 15 parishes, including numerous schools.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06281a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]</ref>\n\nThe Custodian's offices are at the [[Monastery of St Saviour]], a 16th-century Franciscan monastery near [[New Gate]] in the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City of Jerusalem]].\n\n== Activities ==\n\n===Education===\nSchools founded by the Franciscan friars include [[Terra Santa College]] in Nicosia, Cyprus and \nMagnificat Institute in Jerusalem.\n\n===Current issues===\n[[File:Palestinian Christian Scouts Nativity Church in Bethlehem Christmas Eve 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Palestinian Christian]] [[scouts]] on [[Christmas Eve]] in front of the [[Church of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]] (2006).]]\nFr. Pizzaballa expressed concern view that many Christians were leaving the region, especially the [[Palestinian Christians|Christians of the Palestinian Territories]], and that housing assistance was being offered to discourage [[emigration]]. He attributed the exodus to lack of prospects for the future and the political situation.<ref name=Challenge/>\n\nIn 2011, the [[Catholic News Service]] (CNS) website aired an interview on [[Vatican Radio]] in which Father Pizzaballa alluded to the tense situation for Christians in Syria and Egypt.<ref name=\"catholicnews1\"/>\n\n==List of Custodians==\n\n{{Expand list|date=September 2016}}\n* Giuseppe Baldi (1894)\n* Roberto Razz\u00f2li (1906-1912)<ref name=gori>[http://www.terrasanta.net/tsx/assets/pdf/GoriVersioMaiorENG.pdf Paolo Pieraccini, Custos of the Holy Land and Patriarch at the Second Vatican Council]</ref>\n* Ferdinando Diotallevi (1917-1924)<ref name=gori />\n* Aurelio Marotta (1925-1931)<ref name=gori />\n* Nazareno Iacopozzi (1931-1937)<ref name=gori />\n* [[Alberto Gori]] (1937-1949)<ref name=gori />\n* [[Carlo Ceccitelli]] (1986-1992)\n* [[Giuseppe Nazzaro]] (1992-1998)\n* [[Giovanni Battistelli]] (1998-2004)\n* [[Pierbattista Pizzaballa]] (2004\u20132016)\n* [[Francesco Patton]] (2016\u2013)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latin Patriarchate of Jerusalem]]\n* [[Catholic Church in Palestine]]\n* [[Catholic Church in Israel]]\n* [[Palestinian Christians]]\n* [[Holy See\u2013Israel relations]]\n* [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n* [[Brotherhood of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n* [[ATS Association of the Holy Land]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00263206.2012.653139 Masha Halevi, Between Faith and Science: Franciscan Archaeology in the Service of the Holy Places, Middle Eastern Studies, Volume 48, Issue 2, 2012, pp. 249-267]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090106065146/http://custodia.org/ Official website of the Custody of the Holy Land]\n{{Franciscans}}\n{{Francis of Assisi|state=collapsed}}\n{{Old City (Jerusalem)}}\n\n{{coord|31.7791|N|35.2275|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Custody of the Holy Land| ]]\n", "name_user": "Freycris1969", "label": "safe", "comment": "change for order correct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Custody_of_the_Holy_Land"}
{"title_page": "Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)", "text_new": "{{short description|Military unit of the Bangladesh Army}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = ParaCommando Brigade\n| image = \n| image_size = 250px\n| dates = 1971\u2013 present\n| country = {{Flagdeco|Bangladesh }} Bangladesh\n| branch = {{army|Bangladesh}}\n| role = [[Special operations]]\n| motto = ''Do or Die''\n| size = 3 Battalions\n| garrison = Sylhet Cantonment\n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = The Cheetahs\n| patron = \n| colors = Maroon\n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| mascot = Cheetah\n| battles = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] \n* [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict|Chittagong Hill trucks counter-insurgency]]\n* [[United Nations Peacekeeping]]\n* [[Operation Thunderbolt (2016)|Operation Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Operation Twilight in Sylhet]] <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/operation-twilight-sylhet-militant-den-ends-1382671 |title='Operation Twilight' at Sylhet militant den ends |work=The Daily Star|date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[January 2019 Bambari clashes|Operation BEKPA 2]] \n}}\n| anniversaries = \n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = \n| disbanded = \n| commander1 = Brigadier General Muhsin Alam, NDC, PSC<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ispr.gov.bd/\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af-\u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf-\u0995\u09b0\u09cd-2/ |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09c3\u0995 \u09e7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u099f\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a8\u2019\u0995\u09c7 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09be\u09a8 |website=Inter Services Public Relation Directorate |language=bn}}</ref>\n| notable_commanders = \n}}\n\nThe '''Para-Commando Brigade''' is an independent special operations brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]]. The brigade was officially formed on 4 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413 |title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt' |work=The Daily Star |date=3 July 2017 |access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> The brigade got its full structure and strength on 10 October 2019.\n\n==History==\n===Crack Platoon===\nCrack Platoon was a specialized commando unit of Muktibahini during the liberation war of Bangladesh. The commando officer Major [[A.T.M. Haider|A.T.M Haider]] (a former SSG commando in Pakistan Army) formed this unit under the command of sector no-2. Sector commander [[Khaled Mosharraf|Khaled Mosarrof]] personally took care of this unit.\nIn June 1971, commander Khaled made a plan to send commandos in Dhaka city. Because a delegation came from World Bank to visit the East-Pakistan(Now Bangladesh). For that,The Pakistan government was trying to show them, everything was normal in Dhaka. But The commander of sector-2, Khaled Mosarrof was trying to show the whole world that situation was not normal in Dhaka. For that, he along with Commando Major Haider made a plan to launch a commando assault in Dhaka City. They decided to send the specialized platoon-\"Y\" (which was renamed as Crack-Platoon) in Dhaka City. The Commandos successfully launched some operations in Dhaka city and showed the whole world that nothing was normal there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/chronicles/brave-hearts-73724 |title=Brave Hearts |date=27 March 2015 |work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nThe platoon's operations included:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/they-gave-their-today-our-tomorrow-1455394 |title=They gave their today, for our tomorrow |work=The Daily Star |type=Opinion |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n1. [[Operation Hotel Intercontinental]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/operation-hotel-intercontinental-hit-run-53723 |title=Operation Hotel Intercontinental: \"HIT & RUN\" |work=The Daily Star |date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n2. [[Operation Five power stations]]\n\n3. Operation Farmgate\n\n4. Operation Dhanmondi\n\n5. Operation Green road\n\n===Special Warfare Wing===\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Commandos (23113309084).jpg|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando troop at Victory Day Parade 2015.]]\nIn 1976, [[Special Warfare Wing]] was established at Chittagong Cantonment. Later, it was shifted to the [[Jalalabad Cantonment|Sylhet]] cantonment. From then this wing started working under the Bangladesh Army [[School of Infantry and Tactics]] (SI&T). This was the first step towards the formation of a special force in Independent Bangladesh. In 1980, the army commando course and the counter-insurgency course was started in special warfare wing. In the same year, the Special Warfare Wing was expanded to special warfare school. The [[Bangladesh Army Airborne School|Army Airborne School]] was established in 1988 at Sylhet Cantonment under Special Warfare Wing. In 1988, the first para training course was started at the Special Warfare School.\n\n===1st Para-Commando Battalion===\nOn 30 June 1992, the 1st Para-Commando Battalion started its journey at [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] of Sylhet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/stay-alert-deal-unexpected-situation-1485727 |title=Stay alert to deal with unexpected situation |work=The Daily Star |date=3 November 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> The flag of the battalion was raised in May 1993. On 1 June 2015, 1st Para-Commando Battalion came out as a full-fledged regiment. After the formation of ad-hoc [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh Army)|Para-Commando Brigade (PCB)]] on 4 September 2016, they started working under the command of the Brigade.\n\nThe battalion was awarded the national standard on 2 November 2017 as a recognition of their outstanding works.<ref name=\"pcdo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybdnews.net/?p=25355 |script-title=bn:\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb\u09b0\u09be |publisher=Dailybdnews.com |date=2 November 2017 |language=bn |access-date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nUnder this brigade's command, there are three Para-Commando battalions. They are:\n* 1st Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sylhet]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |title=Brig Gen Zahur given Responsibility of CEO (Current Charge), DSE |publisher=[[Dhaka Stock Exchange]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516085801/http://dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2nd Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sreemangal Upazila]], [[Maulavibazar]]\n* 3rd Para-Commando Battalion (Ad-hoc Para-Commando Battalion), [[Sylhet]]\n\nAs typical [[commando]] battalions, these battalions are quite understrength compared to a regular Bangladesh Army infantry battalion, in terms of both manpower and firepower. Each Para-Commando battalion is Consisted of a HQ company and 3 Operations Companies. Each company has separate troops of various specialties i.e. Air Assault, Reconnaissance, Jungle Warfare etc. Battalions also includes of medical, signals and other support personnel, all of whom are airborne and commando qualified.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n;Pistols\n* [[QSZ-92]]\n* [[Bersa Thunder 9]]\n* [[Browning Hi-Power]]\n\n; Sub-machine guns\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n* [[SIG MPX]]\n* [[Kriss Vector|Kriss Vector GEN II]]\n\n;Assault rifles\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 assault rifle]]\n* [[Type 56 assault rifle]]\n* [[Pindad SS2|Pindad SS2-V5]]\n* [[M4 carbine]]\n* [[Steyr AUG]]\n\n;Sniper rifles\n* [[Dragunov sniper rifle]]\n* [[Barrett M82]]\n* [[M24 Sniper Weapon System]]\n* [[Accuracy International Arctic Warfare]]\n* [[Accuracy International AWM]]\n\n;Machine guns and rocket launchers\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 LMG]]\n* [[Type 69 RPG]]\n\n;Transport\n* [[Polaris Inc.|Polaris]] [[All-terrain vehicle]]\n\n== Operations ==\n[[File:02-01-bangladesh-peacekeepers-04.jpg|alt=|thumb|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando member building trust with the locals as part of their UN mission|135x135px]]\n===United Nations peacekeeping===\nBangladesh is participating in different [[United Nations peacekeeping|UN peacekeeping]] missions since 1988. Currently, Bangladesh is one of the largest contributors of the UN peacekeeping operations. Bangladesh Army has deployed its Special Forces in various UN Peacekeeping and Peace Enforcement missions, notably in Ivory Coast, South Sudan, Darfur, Central African Republic, Haiti and Mali. These Special Forces detachments are often tasked with high risk rescue operations and raids against insurgents.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangladeshs-peacekeeping-role-lauded-1688221 |title=Bangladesh's peacekeeping role lauded |work=The Daily Star |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/un-official-praises-bangladeshs-role-1595401 |title=UN official praises Bangladesh's role |work=The Daily Star |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Saha |first=Amity |url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/39719/bangladeshs-role-in-intl-peacekeeping |title=Bangladesh's role in int\u00e2\u20ac\u2122l peacekeeping |work=The Asian Age |location=Dhaka |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Dhaka Holey Artisan Bakery hostage crisis ===\n[[File:Para-Commandos during Operation Thunderbolt.jpg|thumb|171x171px|Para-Commandos in action during <nowiki>''</nowiki>Operation Thunderbolt<nowiki>''</nowiki> at Holey Artisan in Gulshan on the morning of July 2, 2016]]\nOn 1 July 2016, five assailants stormed the Holey Artisan Bakery with crude bombs, machetes, ak 22 rifle and pistols, in Dhaka's affluent neighborhood, [[Gulshan Thana|Gulshan 2]], which is extremely popular among expatriates and foreigners, at roughly 9:20&nbsp;pm, taking hostage of the locals and foreigners inside.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702114529/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |archive-date=2 July 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 July 2016 |title=Bangladesh siege: Twenty killed at Holey Artisan Bakery in Dhaka}}</ref> Not realising the gravity of the situation, the initial assault to secure the premises, commenced by [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]], resulted in the casualties of two police officers in exchanging gunfire with the assailants.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/commandos-storm-dhaka-restaurant-several-hostages-rescued-1.2969719 |publisher=[[CTV News]] |title=Commandos storm Dhaka restaurant, several hostages rescued |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2 July 2016}}</ref> However, Police and the [[Rapid Action Battalion]] acted with celerity in setting up a perimeter around the Bakery to block escape of any assailant.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/03/world/asia/bangladesh-hostage-standoff.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Julfikar Ali |last1=Manik |first2=Geeta |last2=Anand |first3=Ellen |last3=Barry |title=Bangladesh Attack Is New Evidence That ISIS Has Shifted Its Focus Beyond the Mideast}}</ref> After fruitless hours of seeking to bring a peaceful solution to the problem, when the perpetrators refused to communicate with authorities, the realisation set that alternative measures were required.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nAt an early morning meeting on Saturday (2 July), the highest level of Government decided to engage the 1st Commando Battalion. They were flown in from [[Sylhet]] to carry out a counter-assault and free the hostages.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> After gathering intelligence from RAB and the Police forces present on the ground, Commandos initiated their raid (codenamed \"[[2016 Gulshan, Dhaka attack|Operation Thunderbolt]]\"), which began at 7:40&nbsp;am and concluded at 8:30&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |title=20 hostages killed in 'Isil' attack on Dhaka restaurant popular with foreigners |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Andrew |last1=Marszal |first2=Chris |last2=Graham |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701180629/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> They were successfully able to free 13 hostages and kill the assailants.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nDuring the attack, 9 Italians, 7 Japanese, 2 Bangladeshis, 1 Indian, and 1 American were killed by the perpetrators.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\n===Operation Twilight in Sylhet===\nOn Thursday, 23 March 2017, the [[Bangladesh Police]] surrounded a suspected militant hideout in [[Dakshin Surma Upazila]], [[Sylhet]], [[Bangladesh]]. Later, a [[SWAT (Bangladesh)|SWAT team]] joined the police unit from [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Manik |first=Julfikar Ali |last2=Anand |first2=Geeta |date=26 March 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/26/world/asia/bangladeshi-assault-kills-2-militants-but-fails-to-end-standoff.html |title=Bangladeshi Assault Kills 2 Militants but Fails to End Standoff |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The housing complex has two apartment buildings. The Police unit was reinforced with personal from [[Rapid Action Battalion]] on Friday.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/it-seems-the-army-has-settled-for-a-long-haul-in-sylhet-to-neutralise-the-militants |title=It seems the army has settled for a long haul in Sylhet to neutralise the militants |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> On Saturday, the 1st Para Commando Battalion took charge of operations and named it Operation Twilight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Operation Twilight (Bangladesh)|Operation Twilight]] was launched by the 1st Para-Commando Battalion of the adhoc para-commando brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]] under the command of GOC of [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] in [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] Major General [[Anwarul Momen]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143389/Blasts-during-Sylhet-hideout-operation-kill-4 |title=Blasts during Sylhet hideout operation kill 6 |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The main gate of the building was blocked by the militants with a refrigerator with an IED attached to it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/joint-operation-begins-sylhet-militant-den-1381165 |title=3 killed, 31 hurt in blasts outside Sylhet 'militant den' |work=The Daily Star |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The building had 30 apartments and 150 rooms, the militants were constantly changing their location.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/3-killed-sylhet-blasts-1381498 |title=Blasts kill 5 amid raid |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The operation was launched on Saturday morning around 8am. The Commando unit was being assisted by SWAT and Bangladesh Police.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143307/Jt-forces-anti-militant-operation-launched |title=Jt forces' anti-militant 'operation' launched |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> Security forces established a three kilometre perimeter around the militant hideout. The commandos rescued 78 civilians trapped in the building from Thursday.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/gunfire-blasts-heard-as-sylhet-militant-hideout-siege-enters-third-day |title=Gunfire, blasts heard as Sylhet militant hideout siege enters third day |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Two militants were killed in the initial attack, one of who detonated a suicide vest. The militants had planted [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]] all over the building which slowed down the military operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/two-killed-more-well-trained-militants-inside-says-army-in-sylhet-anti-terror-operation |title=Two killed, more \u2018well-trained\u2019 militants inside, says army in Sylhet |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Army spokesman, Brigadier General Fakhrul Ahsan, reported that the operation would take more time because of the presence of IEDs in \"strategic points\" in the building. The Bangladesh Army used RPGs and shells to drive the militants out without much success.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-gunshots-mark-day-3-sylhet-militant-den-raid-1381606 |title=2 militants killed, Sylhet raid to linger: Army |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The commandos also used Armoured Personnel Carriers in the operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/bangladesh-commandos-storm-militants-hideout-in-sylhet-rescue-78-civilians/story-scjqEjp63auHmjsHsTWEpK.html |title=Bangladesh commandos storm militants hideout in Sylhet, rescue 78 civilians |work=Hindustan Times |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Finally four militants were found dead at the hideout.<ref name=\"dailystar1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-firing-heard-sylhet-raid-rolls-day-4-1382035 |title=4 militants dead at Sylhet den: Army |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"dtribune\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/24/live-police-cordon-off-militant-hideout-sylhet/ |title=Live: Four militants killed as Sylhet raid nears end |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Operation BEKPA 2===\nAfter the failure of two countries, Bangladesh Special Forces (BANSF) in the United Nations Peacekeeping Mission has successfully launched an operation against rebel groups in the Central African Republic.\n\nCaptain Tauquir Ahmed of BANSF-3 leads the bloody operation to free the area from rebel party UPC (United municipal La P\u00e9x en Centrifica) with an efficient leadership. At the same time, around 150 prisoners were rescued by the operation.\n===Operation Chiitagong Airport===\nIn 24 February 2019, a Bangladeshi Boeing 737-800 aircraft was hijacked by a gunman on the air. The aircraft was landed to the Chittagong Airport as an emergency landing while it was going to Dubai from Dhaka. A gunman named Palash tried to hijack the aircraft. Though his intention was not clear the authority was trying to negotiate with him. But when everything was failed and then Government ordered the ParaCommando Brigade to Launch an operation. Paracommando brigade members came to the place and launched an operation. The commandos took only eight minutes to make a conclusion. As a result, the hijacker was shoot dead by the commandos, 148 passengers and crew got free from the hostage situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/biman-bangladesh-airlines-plane-hijacker-killed-swift-operation-8-minute-1706659 |title=A swift operation of 8 minutes |work=The Daily Star |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)}}\n\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of Bangladesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Military unit of the Bangladesh Army}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = ParaCommando Brigade\n| image = \n| image_size = 250px\n| dates = 1971\u2013 present\n| country = {{Flagdeco|Bangladesh }} Bangladesh\n| branch = {{army|Bangladesh}}\n| role = [[Special operations]]\n| motto = ''Do or Die''\n| size = 3 Battalions\n| garrison = Sylhet Cantonment\n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = The Cheetahs\n| patron = \n| colors = Maroon\n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| mascot = Cheetah\n| battles = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] \n* [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict|Chittagong Hill trucks counter-insurgency]]\n* [[United Nations Peacekeeping]]\n* [[Operation Thunderbolt (2016)|Operation Thunderbolt]]\n* [[Operation Twilight in Sylhet]] <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/operation-twilight-sylhet-militant-den-ends-1382671 |title='Operation Twilight' at Sylhet militant den ends |work=The Daily Star|date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[January 2019 Bambari clashes|Operation BEKPA 2]] \n}}\n| anniversaries = \n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = \n| disbanded = \n| commander1 = Brigadier General Muhsin Alam, NDC, PSC<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ispr.gov.bd/\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af-\u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf-\u0995\u09b0\u09cd-2/ |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u09b0\u09be\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09c3\u0995 \u09e7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u099f\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a8\u2019\u0995\u09c7 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09be\u09a8 |website=Inter Services Public Relation Directorate |language=bn}}</ref>\n| notable_commanders = \n}}\n\nThe '''Para-Commando Brigade''' is an independent special operations brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]]. The brigade was officially formed on 4 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/dhaka-cafe-attack-recounting-operation-thunderbolt-1427413 |title=Recounting 'Operation Thunderbolt' |work=The Daily Star |date=3 July 2017 |access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> The brigade got its full structure and strength on 10 October 2019.\n\n==History==\n===Crack Platoon===\nCrack Platoon was a specialized commando unit of Muktibahini during the liberation war of Bangladesh. The commando officer Major [[A.T.M. Haider|A.T.M Haider]] (a former SSG commando in Pakistan Army) formed this unit under the command of sector no-2. Sector commander [[Khaled Mosharraf|Khaled Mosarrof]] personally took care of this unit.\nIn June 1971, commander Khaled made a plan to send commandos in Dhaka city. Because a delegation came from World Bank to visit the East-Pakistan(Now Bangladesh). For that,The Pakistan government was trying to show them, everything was normal in Dhaka. But The commander of sector-2, Khaled Mosarrof was trying to show the whole world that situation was not normal in Dhaka. For that, he along with Commando Major Haider made a plan to launch a commando assault in Dhaka City. They decided to send the specialized platoon-\"Y\" (which was renamed as Crack-Platoon) in Dhaka City. The Commandos successfully launched some operations in Dhaka city and showed the whole world that nothing was normal there.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-weekend/chronicles/brave-hearts-73724 |title=Brave Hearts |date=27 March 2015 |work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nThe platoon's operations included:<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/they-gave-their-today-our-tomorrow-1455394 |title=They gave their today, for our tomorrow |work=The Daily Star |type=Opinion |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n1. [[Operation Hotel Intercontinental]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/operation-hotel-intercontinental-hit-run-53723 |title=Operation Hotel Intercontinental: \"HIT & RUN\" |work=The Daily Star |date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n2. [[Operation Five power stations]]\n\n3. Operation Farmgate\n\n4. Operation Dhanmondi\n\n5. Operation Green road\n\n===Special Warfare Wing===\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Army Commandos (23113309084).jpg|thumbnail|right|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando troop at Victory Day Parade 2015.]]\nIn 1976, [[Special Warfare Wing]] was established at Chittagong Cantonment. Later, it was shifted to the [[Jalalabad Cantonment|Sylhet]] cantonment. From then this wing started working under the Bangladesh Army [[School of Infantry and Tactics]] (SI&T). This was the first step towards the formation of a special force in Independent Bangladesh. In 1980, the army commando course and the counter-insurgency course was started in special warfare wing. In the same year, the Special Warfare Wing was expanded to special warfare school. The [[Bangladesh Army Airborne School|Army Airborne School]] was established in 1988 at Sylhet Cantonment under Special Warfare Wing. In 1988, the first para training course was started at the Special Warfare School.\n\n===1st Para-Commando Battalion===\nOn 30 June 1992, the 1st Para-Commando Battalion started its journey at [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] of Sylhet.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/stay-alert-deal-unexpected-situation-1485727 |title=Stay alert to deal with unexpected situation |work=The Daily Star |date=3 November 2017 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> The flag of the battalion was raised in May 1993. On 1 June 2015, 1st Para-Commando Battalion came out as a full-fledged regiment. After the formation of ad-hoc [[Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh Army)|Para-Commando Brigade (PCB)]] on 4 September 2016, they started working under the command of the Brigade.\n\nThe battalion was awarded the national standard on 2 November 2017 as a recognition of their outstanding works.<ref name=\"pcdo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybdnews.net/?p=25355 |script-title=bn:\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09a4\u09be\u0995\u09be \u09aa\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09aa\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be \u0995\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09cb\u09b0\u09be |publisher=Dailybdnews.com |date=2 November 2017 |language=bn |access-date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nUnder this brigade's command, there are three Para-Commando battalions. They are:\n* 1st Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sylhet]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |title=Brig Gen Zahur given Responsibility of CEO (Current Charge), DSE |publisher=[[Dhaka Stock Exchange]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516085801/http://dsebd.org/pdf/COO_September_08_2011.pdf |archive-date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2nd Para-Commando Battalion, headquartered in [[Sreemangal Upazila]], [[Maulavibazar]]\n* 3rd Para-Commando Battalion (Ad-hoc Para-Commando Battalion), [[Sylhet]]\n\nAs typical [[commando]] battalions, these battalions are quite understrength compared to a regular Bangladesh Army infantry battalion, in terms of both manpower and firepower. Each Para-Commando battalion is Consisted of a HQ company and 3 Operations Companies. Each company has separate troops of various specialties i.e. Air Assault, Reconnaissance, Jungle Warfare etc. Battalions also includes of medical, signals and other support personnel, all of whom are airborne and commando qualified.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{unsourced section|date=December 2019}}\n;Pistols\n* [[QSZ-92]]\n* [[Bersa Thunder 9]]\n* [[Browning Hi-Power]]\n\n; Sub-machine guns\n* [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n* [[SIG MPX]]\n* [[Kriss Vector|Kriss Vector GEN II]]\n\n;Assault rifles\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 assault rifle]]\n* [[Type 56 assault rifle]]\n* [[Pindad SS2|Pindad SS2-V5]]\n* [[M4 carbine]]\n* [[Steyr AUG]]\n\n;Sniper rifles\n* [[Dragunov sniper rifle]]\n* [[Barrett M82]]\n* [[M24 Sniper Weapon System]]\n* [[Accuracy International Arctic Warfare]]\n* [[Accuracy International AWM]]\n\n;Machine guns and rocket launchers\n* [[Type 81 assault rifle|BD-08 LMG]]\n* [[Type 69 RPG]]\n\n;Transport\n* [[Polaris Inc.|Polaris]] [[All-terrain vehicle]]\n\n== Operations ==\n===United Nations peacekeeping===\n[[File:02-01-bangladesh-peacekeepers-04.jpg|alt=|thumb|Bangladesh Army Para-Commando member building trust with the locals as part of their UN mission]]\nBangladesh is participating in different [[United Nations peacekeeping|UN peacekeeping]] missions since 1988. Currently, Bangladesh is one of the largest contributors of the UN peacekeeping operations. Bangladesh Army has deployed its Special Forces in various UN Peacekeeping and Peace Enforcement missions, notably in Ivory Coast, South Sudan, Darfur, Central African Republic, Haiti and Mali. These Special Forces detachments are often tasked with high risk rescue operations and raids against insurgents.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/bangladeshs-peacekeeping-role-lauded-1688221 |title=Bangladesh's peacekeeping role lauded |work=The Daily Star |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/un-official-praises-bangladeshs-role-1595401 |title=UN official praises Bangladesh's role |work=The Daily Star |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Saha |first=Amity |url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/39719/bangladeshs-role-in-intl-peacekeeping |title=Bangladesh's role in int\u00e2\u20ac\u2122l peacekeeping |work=The Asian Age |location=Dhaka |access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Dhaka Holey Artisan Bakery hostage crisis ===\nOn 1 July 2016, five assailants stormed the Holey Artisan Bakery with crude bombs, machetes, ak 22 rifle and pistols, in Dhaka's affluent neighborhood, [[Gulshan Thana|Gulshan 2]], which is extremely popular among expatriates and foreigners, at roughly 9:20&nbsp;pm, taking hostage of the locals and foreigners inside.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702114529/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |archive-date=2 July 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36692613 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 July 2016 |title=Bangladesh siege: Twenty killed at Holey Artisan Bakery in Dhaka}}</ref> Not realising the gravity of the situation, the initial assault to secure the premises, commenced by [[Dhaka Metropolitan Police]], resulted in the casualties of two police officers in exchanging gunfire with the assailants.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/commandos-storm-dhaka-restaurant-several-hostages-rescued-1.2969719 |publisher=[[CTV News]] |title=Commandos storm Dhaka restaurant, several hostages rescued |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2 July 2016}}</ref> However, Police and the [[Rapid Action Battalion]] acted with celerity in setting up a perimeter around the Bakery to block escape of any assailant.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/03/world/asia/bangladesh-hostage-standoff.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Julfikar Ali |last1=Manik |first2=Geeta |last2=Anand |first3=Ellen |last3=Barry |title=Bangladesh Attack Is New Evidence That ISIS Has Shifted Its Focus Beyond the Mideast}}</ref> After fruitless hours of seeking to bring a peaceful solution to the problem, when the perpetrators refused to communicate with authorities, the realisation set that alternative measures were required.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nAt an early morning meeting on Saturday (2 July), the highest level of Government decided to engage the 1st Commando Battalion. They were flown in from [[Sylhet]] to carry out a counter-assault and free the hostages.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> After gathering intelligence from RAB and the Police forces present on the ground, Commandos initiated their raid (codenamed \"[[2016 Gulshan, Dhaka attack|Operation Thunderbolt]]\"), which began at 7:40&nbsp;am and concluded at 8:30&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |title=20 hostages killed in 'Isil' attack on Dhaka restaurant popular with foreigners |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 July 2016 |first1=Andrew |last1=Marszal |first2=Chris |last2=Graham |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701180629/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/01/gunmen-attack-restaurant-in-diplomatic-quarter-of-bangladeshi-ca/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> They were successfully able to free 13 hostages and kill the assailants.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" />\n\nDuring the attack, 9 Italians, 7 Japanese, 2 Bangladeshis, 1 Indian, and 1 American were killed by the perpetrators.<ref name=\"BBC\" /><ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\n===Operation Twilight in Sylhet===\nOn Thursday, 23 March 2017, the [[Bangladesh Police]] surrounded a suspected militant hideout in [[Dakshin Surma Upazila]], [[Sylhet]], [[Bangladesh]]. Later, a [[SWAT (Bangladesh)|SWAT team]] joined the police unit from [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Manik |first=Julfikar Ali |last2=Anand |first2=Geeta |date=26 March 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/26/world/asia/bangladeshi-assault-kills-2-militants-but-fails-to-end-standoff.html |title=Bangladeshi Assault Kills 2 Militants but Fails to End Standoff |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The housing complex has two apartment buildings. The Police unit was reinforced with personal from [[Rapid Action Battalion]] on Friday.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/it-seems-the-army-has-settled-for-a-long-haul-in-sylhet-to-neutralise-the-militants |title=It seems the army has settled for a long haul in Sylhet to neutralise the militants |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> On Saturday, the 1st Para Commando Battalion took charge of operations and named it Operation Twilight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Operation Twilight (Bangladesh)|Operation Twilight]] was launched by the 1st Para-Commando Battalion of the adhoc para-commando brigade of the [[Bangladesh Army]] under the command of GOC of [[17th Infantry Division (Bangladesh)|17th Infantry Division]] in [[Jalalabad Cantonment]] Major General [[Anwarul Momen]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143389/Blasts-during-Sylhet-hideout-operation-kill-4 |title=Blasts during Sylhet hideout operation kill 6 |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> The main gate of the building was blocked by the militants with a refrigerator with an IED attached to it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/joint-operation-begins-sylhet-militant-den-1381165 |title=3 killed, 31 hurt in blasts outside Sylhet 'militant den' |work=The Daily Star |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The building had 30 apartments and 150 rooms, the militants were constantly changing their location.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/3-killed-sylhet-blasts-1381498 |title=Blasts kill 5 amid raid |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The operation was launched on Saturday morning around 8am. The Commando unit was being assisted by SWAT and Bangladesh Police.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/143307/Jt-forces-anti-militant-operation-launched |title=Jt forces' anti-militant 'operation' launched |work=Prothom Alo |access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> Security forces established a three kilometre perimeter around the militant hideout. The commandos rescued 78 civilians trapped in the building from Thursday.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/gunfire-blasts-heard-as-sylhet-militant-hideout-siege-enters-third-day |title=Gunfire, blasts heard as Sylhet militant hideout siege enters third day |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Two militants were killed in the initial attack, one of who detonated a suicide vest. The militants had planted [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]] all over the building which slowed down the military operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/03/26/two-killed-more-well-trained-militants-inside-says-army-in-sylhet-anti-terror-operation |title=Two killed, more \u2018well-trained\u2019 militants inside, says army in Sylhet |work=bdnews24.com |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Army spokesman, Brigadier General Fakhrul Ahsan, reported that the operation would take more time because of the presence of IEDs in \"strategic points\" in the building. The Bangladesh Army used RPGs and shells to drive the militants out without much success.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-gunshots-mark-day-3-sylhet-militant-den-raid-1381606 |title=2 militants killed, Sylhet raid to linger: Army |work=The Daily Star |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The commandos also used Armoured Personnel Carriers in the operation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/bangladesh-commandos-storm-militants-hideout-in-sylhet-rescue-78-civilians/story-scjqEjp63auHmjsHsTWEpK.html |title=Bangladesh commandos storm militants hideout in Sylhet, rescue 78 civilians |work=Hindustan Times |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Finally four militants were found dead at the hideout.<ref name=\"dailystar1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/sporadic-firing-heard-sylhet-raid-rolls-day-4-1382035 |title=4 militants dead at Sylhet den: Army |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"dtribune\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/24/live-police-cordon-off-militant-hideout-sylhet/ |title=Live: Four militants killed as Sylhet raid nears end |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Operation BEKPA 2===\nAfter the failure of two countries, Bangladesh Special Forces (BANSF) in the United Nations Peacekeeping Mission has successfully launched an operation against rebel groups in the Central African Republic.\n\nCaptain Tauquir Ahmed of BANSF-3 leads the bloody operation to free the area from rebel party UPC (United municipal La P\u00e9x en Centrifica) with an efficient leadership. At the same time, around 150 prisoners were rescued by the operation.\n===Operation Chiitagong Airport===\nIn 24 February 2019, a Bangladeshi Boeing 737-800 aircraft was hijacked by a gunman on the air. The aircraft was landed to the Chittagong Airport as an emergency landing while it was going to Dubai from Dhaka. A gunman named Palash tried to hijack the aircraft. Though his intention was not clear the authority was trying to negotiate with him. But when everything was failed and then Government ordered the ParaCommando Brigade to Launch an operation. Paracommando brigade members came to the place and launched an operation. The commandos took only eight minutes to make a conclusion. As a result, the hijacker was shoot dead by the commandos, 148 passengers and crew got free from the hostage situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/biman-bangladesh-airlines-plane-hijacker-killed-swift-operation-8-minute-1706659 |title=A swift operation of 8 minutes |work=The Daily Star |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Para-Commando Brigade (Bangladesh)}}\n\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of Bangladesh]]\n", "name_user": "Squad 71", "label": "safe", 